{"title_page": "Religious views of Isaac Newton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg|thumb|Sir Isaac Newton at 46 in [[Godfrey Kneller]]'s 1689 portrait.]]\n{{Isaac Newton sidebar}}\n\n[[Isaac Newton]] (4 January 1643 \u2013 31 March 1727)<ref name=\"Christianson\">{{cite book |first=Gale E. |last=Christianson | url =https://archive.org/details/isaacnewtonscie00chri |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/isaacnewtonscie00chri/page/74 74] | title =  Isaac Newton and the scientific revolution | publisher = \u2013 155 pages Oxford portraits in science Oxford University Press|date= 19 September 1996| accessdate =  28 January 2012|isbn=0-19-509224-4}}</ref> was considered an insightful and erudite theologian by his contemporaries.<ref>{{citation|jstor=2708258|title=Isaac Newton on Science and Religion|journal=Journal of the History of Ideas|volume=31|issue=4|pages=521\u2013542|last1=Austin|first1=William H.|year=1970|doi=10.2307/2708258}}</ref><ref name=\"Iliffe & Mandelbrote \">[ENGLISH & LATIN] {{cite web | url =http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=73 | title =The Newton Project ''Newton's Views on the Corruptions of Scripture and the Church''  | accessdate = 28 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Iliffe\">[http://www.sussex.ac.uk/profiles/200167 Professor Rob Iliffe] (AHRC Newton Papers Project)  THE NEWTON PROJECT \u2013 ''Newton's Religious Writings''  [ENGLISH & LATIN] {{cite book | url =http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=44| title =  prism.php44 | publisher = University of Sussex| accessdate = 28 January 2012}}</ref> He wrote many works that would now be classified as [[Isaac Newton's occult studies|occult studies]] and [[religious tracts]] dealing with the [[Biblical literalism|literal interpretation of the Bible]].<ref name=newtonproject>{{cite web| title = Newton's Views on Prophecy  | publisher = The Newton Project  | date = 5 April 2007  | url = http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=74  | accessdate = 15 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nNewton's conception of the physical world provided a stable model of the natural world that would reinforce stability and harmony in the civic world. <!--The [[law of gravity]] became Newton's best-known discovery, but--> Newton saw a [[monotheistic God]] as the masterful creator whose existence could not be denied in the face of the grandeur of all creation.<ref name=\"Principia, Book III 1953\">Principia, Book III; cited in; Newton's Philosophy of Nature: Selections from his writings, p. 42, ed. H.S. Thayer, Hafner Library of Classics, NY, 1953.</ref><ref>A Short Scheme of the True Religion, manuscript quoted in Memoirs of the Life, Writings and Discoveries of Sir Isaac Newton by Sir David Brewster, Edinburgh, 1850; cited in; ibid, p. 65.</ref> Although born into an [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] family, by his thirties Newton held a [[Christian faith]] that, had it been made public, would not have been considered orthodox by mainstream [[Christianity]],<ref name=\"Newton - 1\">[[Richard S. Westfall]] \u2013 [[Indiana University]] {{cite book | url =http://galileo.rice.edu/Catalog/NewFiles/newton.html   | title = The Galileo Project   | publisher = ([[Rice University]]) | accessdate = 5 July 2008}}</ref> with one modern historian labeling him a [[heresy|heretic]].<ref name=\"heretic\">{{cite journal |last=Snobelen |first=Stephen D. |authorlink=Stephen Snobelen |title=Isaac Newton, heretic : the strategies of a Nicodemite |journal=British Journal for the History of Science |volume=32 |pages=381\u2013419 |year=1999 |url=http://www.toriah.org/articles/snobelen-1999-1.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908043029/http://www.toriah.org/articles/snobelen-1999-1.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2014 |doi=10.1017/S0007087499003751 |issue=4 }}</ref>\n\n==Christian orthodoxy==\nNewton was born into an Anglican family three months after the death of his father, a prosperous farmer also named Isaac Newton. When Newton was three, his mother married the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)#Anglican churches|rector]] of the neighbouring parish of [[North Witham]] and went to live with her new husband, the Reverend Barnabus Smith, leaving her son in the care of his maternal grandmother, Margery Ayscough.<ref>{{cite book\n|title=Illustrations of the literary history of the eighteenth century: Consisting of authentic memoirs and original letters of eminent persons; and intended as a sequel to the Literary anecdotes, Volume 4 |first1=John Bowyer |last1=Nichols |publisher=Nichols, Son, and Bentley |year=1822 |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_pBEUAAAAQAAJ/page/n56 32] |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_pBEUAAAAQAAJ}}</ref> Isaac apparently hated his step-father, and had nothing to do with Smith during his childhood.<ref name=\"Newton - 1\"/> His maternal uncle, the rector serving the parish of [[Burton Coggles]],<ref>{{cite book|author=C. D. Broad|authorlink=C. D. Broad|title=Ethics and the History of Philosophy: Selected Essays|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mccz8hwkfvgC&pg=PA3|volume=Volume 1|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-22530-4|page=3}}</ref> was involved to some extent in the care of Isaac.\n\nIn 1667 Newton became a Fellow of [[Trinity College, Cambridge]],<ref>[[Cambridge University]] [https://archive.is/20120715113444/http://venn.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/search.pl?sur=Newton&suro=c&fir=Isaac&firo=c&cit=&cito=c&c=all&tex=&sye=&eye=&col=all&maxcount=50 Alumni Database] Retrieved 29 January 2012</ref> making necessary his commitment to taking [[Holy Orders]] within seven years of completing his [[Master of Arts|MA]], which he did the following year. He was also required to take a vow of celibacy and recognize the [[Thirty-Nine Articles]] of the Church of England.<ref name=\"Iliffe-2\">Professor Rob Iliffe (AHRC Newton Papers Project) THE NEWTON PROJECT {{cite book | url =http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=15| title =  prism.php15 | publisher = University of Sussex| accessdate = 7 February 2012}}</ref> Newton considered ceasing his studies prior to completion in order to avoid the ordination made necessary by law of [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]].<ref name=\"Cambridge \">[[Cambridge University Library]] {{cite book | url =https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:8bhDeW5cfrYJ:www.lib.cam.ac.uk/exhibitions/Footprints_of_the_Lion/scholar.pdf+Newton+on+Maimonides&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgKghLb5qt9p3T_uupTyiiQnW__s-6Bx0xOZrHx4H3wChat3we54G4ciNJ2I7D_O69Rl_w7B12E_R0-VjP1tUOrJlF88_maweWYap1SQeK5bOj5e9jipxm9mSbrPhnRiDch9mlK&sig=AHIEtbSJEIrnGcjqkfWUiIfmCafcyyQJfA |title= .ac| accessdate =  29 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\" Christianson  \"/> He was eventually successful in avoiding the statute, assisted in this by the efforts of [[Isaac Barrow]], as in 1676 the then [[Secretary of State for the Northern Department]], [[Joseph Williamson (English politician)|Joseph Williamson]], changed the relevant statute of Trinity College to provide dispensation from this duty.<ref name=\"Iliffe-2\"/> After taking advantage of that, Newton embarked on an investigative study of the early history of the Church, which developed, during the 1680s, into inquiries about the origins of religion. At around the same time, he developed a scientific view on motion and matter.<ref name=\"Cambridge\"/> Of ''[[Philosophi\u00e6 Naturalis Principia Mathematica]]'' he stated:<ref>S.D.Snobelen ([[University of King's College]]) \u2013 ''To Discourse of God : Isaac Newton's Heterdox Theology and Natural Philosophy'' [https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:O3EkKGIo9uwJ:www.isaac-newton.org/pdf/Snobelen%2520Newton%2520To%2520discourse%2520of%2520God%25202004.pdf+Newton+at+Cambridge+theology&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShNj3l0Oaf79xt3TGwPIh534c9N1-zNZsRLhkIn1vnWZ7M9mCXjGnqIIGwz4_Zb1WYv_DG_r12lg4-KouEDVIiiACxJCnyu88V9ZTQ_w8bORXoBVZsT9RGDH_gMH5gPUxY7BZFm&sig=AHIEtbSzLx1OAvnyKCX1UZB7GlgCmzA63Q Nova Scotia] Retrieved 29 January 2012</ref>\n{{quote|When I wrote my treatise about our Systeme I had an eye upon such Principles as might work with considering men for the beliefe of a Deity and nothing can rejoyce me more than to find it useful for that purpose.}}\n\n\nAccording to most scholars, Newton was [[Arianism|Arian]], not holding to [[Trinity|Trinitarianism]].<ref name=\"heretic\"/><ref name=dulles/><ref name=\"neveratrest\">Richard Westfall, '' Never at Rest: A Biography of Isaac Newton,'' (1980) pp. 103, 25.</ref> As well as being [[Nontrinitarianism|antitrinitarian]], Newton allegedly rejected the orthodox doctrines of the [[Immortality of the soul|immortal soul]],<ref name=\"heretic\"/> a personal [[devil]] and literal [[demon]]s.<ref name=\"heretic\"/> Although he was not a [[Socinianism|Socinian]] he shared many similar beliefs with them.<ref name=\"heretic\"/> A manuscript he sent to [[John Locke]] in which he disputed the existence of the [[Trinity]] was never published. In a minority view, T.C. Pfizenmaier argued Newton was neither \"orthodox\" nor an Arian,<ref>Pfizenmaier, T.C, \"The Trinitarian Theology of Dr. Samuel Clarke\" (1675\u20131729)</ref> but that, rather, Newton believed both of these groups had wandered into metaphysical speculation.<ref name=\"arian?\">Pfizenmaier, T.C., \"Was Isaac Newton an Arian?\" Journal of the History of Ideas 68(1):57\u201380, 1997.</ref> Pfizenmaier also argued that Newton held closer to the [[Semi-Arian]] view of the Trinity that [[Jesus Christ]] was of a \"similar substance\" ([[homoiousios]]) from the Father rather than the orthodox view that Jesus Christ is of the \"same substance\" of the Father ([[homoousios]]) as endorsed by modern [[Eastern Orthodox]], [[Roman Catholics]] and [[Protestant]]s.<ref name=\"arian?\"/> [[Stephen Snobelen|S. D. Snobelen]] has also argued against this from manuscripts produced late in Newton's life which demonstrate Newton rejected the Eastern view of the Trinity.<ref name=\"heretic\"/>\n\nNewton refused [[Viaticum]] before his death.<ref name=\"Newton - 1\"/>\n\n==God as masterful creator==\nNewton saw God as the masterful creator whose existence could not be denied in the face of the grandeur of all creation.<ref>Webb, R.K. ed. Knud Haakonssen. \"The emergence of Rational Dissent.\" Enlightenment and Religion: Rational Dissent in eighteenth-century Britain. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge: 1996. p19.</ref> Nevertheless, he rejected [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]]'s thesis that God would necessarily make a perfect world which requires no intervention from the creator. In Query 31 of the ''Opticks'', Newton simultaneously made an argument from design and for the necessity of intervention:\n{{quote| For while comets move in very eccentric orbs in all manner of positions, blind fate could never make all the planets move one and the same way in orbs concentric, some inconsiderable irregularities excepted which may have arisen from the mutual actions of comets and planets on one another, and which will be apt to increase, till this system wants a reformation.<ref>Newton, 1706 ''Opticks'' (2nd Edition), quoted in H. G. Alexander 1956 (ed): ''The Leibniz-Clarke correspondence'', University of Manchester Press.</ref>}}\nThis passage prompted an attack by Leibniz in a letter to his friend [[Caroline of Ansbach]]:\n{{quote|Sir Isaac Newton and his followers have also a very odd opinion concerning the work of God. According to their doctrine, God Almighty wants to wind up his watch from time to time: otherwise it would cease to move. He had not, it seems, sufficient foresight to make it a perpetual motion.<ref>Leibniz, first letter, in Alexander 1956, p. 11</ref>}}\nLeibniz's letter initiated the [[Leibniz-Clarke correspondence]], ostensibly with Newton's friend and disciple [[Samuel Clarke]], although as Caroline wrote, Clarke's letters \"are not written without the advice of the Chev. Newton\".<ref>Caroline to Leibniz, 10 January 1716, quoted in Alexander 1956, p. 193. (Chev. = Chevalier i.e. Knight.)</ref>\nClarke complained that Leibniz's concept of God as a \"supra-mundane intelligence\" who set up a \"pre-established harmony\" was only a step from atheism: \"And as those men, who pretend that in an earthly government things may go on perfectly well without the king himself ordering or disposing of any thing, may reasonably be suspected that they would like very well to set the king aside: so, whosoever contends, that the beings of the world can go on without the continual direction of God...his doctrine does in effect tend to exclude God out of the world\".<ref>Clarke, first reply, in Alexander 1956 p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn addition to stepping in to re-form the solar system, Newton invoked God's active intervention to prevent the stars falling in on each other, and perhaps in preventing the amount of motion in the universe from decaying due to viscosity and friction.<ref>H.W. Alexander 1956, p. xvii</ref> In private correspondence Newton sometimes hinted that the force of Gravity was due to an immaterial influence:\n{{quote|Tis inconceivable that inanimate brute matter should (without the mediation of something else which is not material) operate upon & affect other matter without mutual contact.<ref>Newton to Bentley, 25 February 1693</ref>}}\nLeibniz jibed that such an immaterial influence would be a continual miracle; this was another strand of his debate with Clarke.\n\nNewton's view has been considered to be close to [[deism]] and several biographers and scholars labelled him as a deist who is strongly influenced by Christianity.<ref>{{cite book|title=Essays on the Context, Nature, and Influence of Isaac Newton's Theology|year=1990|publisher=Springer|isbn=9780792305835|first=James E.|last= Force|first2= Richard Henry |last2=Popkin|editor-first=James E. |editor-last=Force|editor2-first= Richard Henry |editor2-last=Popkin|page=53|quote=Newton has often been identified as a deist. ...In the 19th century, William Blake seems to have put Newton into the deistic camp. Scholars in the 20th-century have often continued to view Newton as a deist. Gerald R. Cragg views Newton as a kind of proto-deist and, as evidence, points to Newton's belief in a true, original, monotheistic religion first discovered in ancient times by natural reason. This position, in Cragg's view, leads to the elimination of the Christian revelation as neither necessary nor sufficient for human knowledge of God. This agenda is indeed the key point, as Leland describes above, of the deistic program which seeks to \"set aside\" revelatory religious texts. Cragg writes that, \"In effect, Newton ignored the claims of revelation and pointed in a direction which many eighteenth-century thinkers would willingly follow.\" John Redwood has also recently linked anti-Trinitarian theology with both \"Newtonianism\" and \"deism.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Innermost Kernel: Depth Psychology and Quantum Physics. Wolfgang Pauli's Dialogue with C.G. Jung|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783540208563|pages=181\u2013182|first=Suzanne |last=Gieser|quote=Newton seems to have been closer to the deists in his conception of God and had no time for the doctrine of the Trinity. The deists did not recognize the divine nature of Christ. According to Fierz, Newton's conception of God permeated his entire scientific work: God's universality and eternity express themselves in the dominion of the laws of nature. Time and space are regarded as the 'organs' of God. All is contained and moves in God but without having any effect on God himself. Thus space and time become metaphysical entities, superordinate existences that are not associated with any interaction, activity or observation on man's part.|date=14 February 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Classical Mechanics: Transformations, Flows, Integrable and Chaotic Dynamics|year=1997|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521578820|first=Joseph L. |last=McCauley|page=3|quote=Newton (1642\u20131727), as a seventeenth century nonChristian Deist, would have been susceptible to an accusation of heresy by either the Anglican Church or the Puritans.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Philosophical problems of modern physics|year=1982|publisher=Reidel|editor=Hans S. Plendl|page=361|quote=Newton expressed the same conception of the nature of atoms in his deistic view of the Universe.}}</ref> However, he differed from strict adherents of deism in that he invoked God as a special physical cause to keep the planets in orbits.<ref name=dulles>Avery Cardinal Dulles. [http://www.firstthings.com/article.php3?id_article=143 The Deist Minimum]. 2005.</ref> He warned against using the [[law of gravity]] to view the universe as a mere machine, like a great clock. He said:\n\n{{quote|This most beautiful system of the sun, planets, and comets, could only proceed from the counsel and dominion of an intelligent Being. [...] This Being governs all things, not as the soul of the world, but as Lord over all; and on account of his dominion he is wont to be called \"Lord God\" \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03c9\u03c1 [pantokrat\u014dr], or \"Universal Ruler\". [...] The Supreme God is a Being eternal, infinite, [and] absolutely perfect.<ref name=\"Principia, Book III 1953\"/>}}\n\n{{quote|Opposition to godliness is atheism in profession and idolatry in practice. Atheism is so senseless and odious to mankind that it never had many professors.<ref>Brewster, Sir David. ''A Short Scheme of the True Religion, manuscript quoted in Memoirs of the Life, Writings and Discoveries of Sir Isaac Newton'' Edinburgh, 1850.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/view/texts/normalized/THEM00007|title=A short Schem of the true Religion|website=The Newton Project|publisher=[[University of Sussex]]|location=East Sussex|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GRWuKYu6?url=http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/view/texts/normalized/THEM00007|archivedate=7 May 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nOn the other hand, [[latitudinarian]] and Newtonian ideas taken too far resulted in the millenarians, a religious faction dedicated to the concept of a mechanical universe, but finding in it the same enthusiasm and mysticism that the Enlightenment had fought so hard to extinguish.<ref name=\"jacob\">Jacob, Margaret C. The Newtonians and the English Revolution: 1689\u20131720.</ref> Newton himself may have had some interest in [[millenarianism]] as he wrote about both the [[Book of Daniel]] and the [[Book of Revelation]] in his [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16878/16878-h/16878-h.htm Observations Upon the Prophecies].\n\nNewton's conception of the physical world provided a stable model of the natural world that would reinforce stability and harmony in the civic world.<ref name=\"jacob\" />\n\n==The Bible==\n\nNewton spent a great deal of time trying to discover [[Bible code|hidden messages within the Bible]].  After 1690, Newton wrote a number of [[religious tracts]] dealing with the literal interpretation of the [[Bible]]. In a manuscript Newton wrote in 1704 he describes his attempts to extract scientific information from the Bible. He estimated that the world would end no earlier than 2060. In predicting this he said \"This I mention not to assert when the time of the end shall be, but to put a stop to the rash conjectures of fanciful men who are frequently predicting the time of the end, and by doing so bring the sacred prophesies into discredit as often as their predictions fail.\"<ref name=\"paper\">{{cite news |title=Papers Show Isaac Newton's Religious Side, Predict Date of Apocalypse |agency=Associated Press |date=19 June 2007 |url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20070619/28049_Papers_Show_Isaac_Newton%27s_Religious_Side%2C_Predict_Date_of_Apocalypse.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070629231937/http://www.christianpost.com/article/20070619/28049_Papers_Show_Isaac_Newton's_Religious_Side,_Predict_Date_of_Apocalypse.htm |archivedate=29 June 2007 |accessdate=17 May 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Library of Trinity College, Cambridge, holds in its collections Newton's personal copy of the King James Version, which exhibits numerous marginal notes in his hand as well as about 500 reader's marks pointing to passages of particular interest to him. A note is attached to the Bible indicating that it \"was given by Sir Isaac Newton in his last illness to the woman who nursed him\". The book was eventually bequeathed to the Library in 1878. The places Newton marked or annotated in his Bible bear witness to his investigations into theology, chronology, alchemy, and natural philosophy; and some of these actually relate to passages of the ''General Scholium'' to the second edition of the ''Principia''. Some other passages he marked offer glimpses of his devotional practices and reveal distinct tensions in his personality. Newton's Bible appears to have been first and foremost a customized reference tool in the hands of a biblical scholar and critic.<ref>Joalland, Michael. \"Isaac Newton Reads the King James Version: The Marginal Notes and Reading Marks of a Natural Philosopher\". ''Papers of the Bibliographical Society of America'', vol. 113, no. 3 (2019): 297\u2013339 (https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/704518?journalCode=pbsa)</ref>\n\n===Prophecy===\nNewton relied upon the existing Scripture for prophecy, believing his interpretations would set the record straight in the face of what he considered to be, \"so little understood\".<ref>{{cite web  | last = Newton  | first = Isaac  | title = The First Book Concerning the Language of the Prophets  | publisher = The Newton Project  | date = 5 April 2007  | url = http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/texts/viewtext.php?id=THEM00005&mode=normalized  | accessdate = 15 August 2007  | url-status = dead  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108210637/http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/texts/viewtext.php?id=THEM00005&mode=normalized  | archivedate = 8 November 2007  | df = dmy-all  }}</ref> Though he would never write a cohesive body of work on Prophecy, Newton's beliefs would lead him to write several treatises on the subject, including an unpublished guide for prophetic interpretation titled ''Rules for interpreting the words & language in Scripture''. In this manuscript he details the necessary requirements for what he considered to be the proper interpretation of the Bible.\n\n===End of The World vs Start of The Millennial Kingdom===\n\nIn his posthumously-published ''Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel, and the Apocalypse of St. John'', Newton expressed his belief that Bible prophecy would not be understood \"until the time of the end\", and that even then \"none of the wicked shall understand\". Referring to that as a future time (\"the last age, the age of opening these things, be now approaching\"), Newton also anticipated \"the general preaching of the Gospel be approaching\" and \"the Gospel must first be preached in all nations before the great tribulation, and end of the world\".<ref>''Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel, and the Apocalypse of St. John'' by Sir Isaac Newton, 1733, J. DARBY and T. BROWNE, [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16878/16878-h/16878-h.htm#NtpJohI_41 Online]</ref>\n\nOver the years, a large amount of media attention and public interest has circulated regarding largely unknown and unpublished documents, evidently written by Isaac Newton, that indicate he believed the world could end in 2060. While Newton also had many other possible dates (e.g. 2034),<ref name=Snobelen>{{cite web\n  | last = Snobelen  | first = Stephen D  | title = Statement on the date 2060  | url = http://www.isaac-newton.org/update.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015054011/http://www.isaac-newton.org/update.html  |archivedate=15 October 2013| accessdate = 4 February 2014}}</ref> he did not believe that the end of the world would take place specifically in 2060.<ref>[http://cjhistory.synergiesprairies.ca/cjhistory/index.php/cjhistory/article/view/8886 \"A time and times and the dividing of times\": Isaac Newton, the Apocalypse and 2060 AD Snobelen, S Can J Hist (2003) vol 38] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221074953/http://cjhistory.synergiesprairies.ca/cjhistory/index.php/cjhistory/article/view/8886 |date=21 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nLike most Protestant theologians of his time, Newton believed that the Papal Office (and not any one particular Pope) was the fulfillment of the Biblical predictions about [[Antichrist]], whose rule was predicted to last for 1,260 years. They applied the [[day-year principle]] (in which a day represents a year in prophecy) to certain key verses in the books of Daniel<ref>the \"time, times and half a time\" of Daniel 7:25 and 12:7</ref> and Revelation<ref>the \"42 months\" of Revelation 11:2 and 13:5 equals the \"1260 days\" of Revelation 11:3 and 12:6</ref> (also known as the Apocalypse), and looked for significant dates in the Papacy's rise to power to begin this timeline. Newton's calculation ending in 2060 is based on the 1,260-year timeline commencing in 800 AD when [[Charlemagne]] became the first Holy Roman Emperor and reconfirmed the earlier (756 AD) [[Donation of Pepin]] to the Papacy.<ref name=\"paper\"/>\n\n=== 2016 vs 2060 ===\n\nHowever, between the time he wrote his 2060 prediction (about 1704) until his death in 1727 Newton conversed, both first hand and by correspondence, with other famous theologians of his time. Those contemporaries who knew him during the remaining 23 years of his life appear to be in agreement that Newton, and the \"best interpreters\" including [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards]], [[Robert Fleming the younger|Robert Fleming]], [[Moses Lowman]], [[Phillip Doddridge]], and Bishop [[Thomas Newton]], were eventually \"pretty well agreed\" that the 1,260-year timeline should be calculated from the year 756 AD.<ref>Jonathan Edwards \u201dHistory of Redemption\" New York: T. and J. Swords (1793) page 431: \"The Beginning of the reign of Antichrist.] The best interpreters (as Mr. Fleming, Sir I. Newton, Mr. Lowman, Dr. Doddridge, Bp. Newton, and Mr. Reader) are pretty well agreed that this reign is to be dated from about A. D. 756, when the Pope began to be a temporal power, (that is, in prophetic language, a beast) by assuming temporal dominion; 1260 years from this period will bring us to about A. D. 2000, and about the 6000th year of the world, which agrees with a tradition at least as ancient as the epistle ascribed to the apostle Barnabas (f 15.] which says, that \" in six thousand years shall all things be accomplished.\"</ref>\n\nF.A. Cox also confirmed that this was the view of Newton and others, including himself:\n\n{{bquote | ''\"The author adopts the hypothesis of Fleming, Sir Isaac Newton, and Lowman, that the 1260 years commenced in A.d. 756; and consequently that the millennium will not begin till the year 2016\".''<ref>Rev. F.A. Cox \"Outlines of Lectures on the Book of Daniel\" London: Westley and Davis (1833) 2nd Edition Page 152</ref>}}\n\n[[Thomas Williams (1755\u20131839)|Thomas Williams]] stated that this timeline had become the predominant view among the leading Protestant theologians of his time:\n\n{{bquote | ''\"Mr. Lowman, though an earlier commentator, is (we believe) far more generally followed ; and he commences the 1260 days from about 756, when, by aid of Pepin, King of France, the Pope obtained considerable temporalities. This carries on the reign of Popery to 2016, or sixteen years into the commencement of the Millennium, as it is generally reckoned\".''<ref>Thomas Williams \"The Cottage Bible and family expositor\" Hartford: D.F. Robinson and H. F. Sumner (1837) Vol. 2-page 1417</ref>}}\n \nIn April of 756 AD, [[Pepin the Short|Pepin]], King of France, accompanied by [[Pope Stephen II]] entered northern Italy, forcing the Lombard King [[Aistulf]] to lift his siege of Rome, and return to [[Pavia]]. Following Aistulf's capitulation, Pepin gave the newly conquered territories to the Papacy by means of the [[Donation of Pepin]], thereby elevating the Pope from being a subject of the [[Byzantine Empire]] to [[head of state]], with [[temporal power (papal)|temporal power]] over the newly constituted [[Papal States]].\n\nThe end of the timeline is based on Daniel 8:25 which reads ''\"...but he shall be broken without hand\"'' and is understood to mean that the end of the Papacy will not be caused by any human action.<ref>Bishop Thomas Newton \"DISSERTATIONS ON THE PROPHECIES\" London: J.F. and C. Rivington (1789) 8th Edition Page 327: \"As the stone in Nebuchadnezzar's dream was cut out of the mountain without hands, that is not by human, but by supernatural means; so the little horn shall be broken without hand, not die the common death, not fall by the hand of men, but perish by a stroke from heaven.\"</ref> Volcanic activity is described as the means by which Rome will be overthrown.<ref>East Apthorp, D.D. \"Discourses on Prophecy\" (1786) Discourse XI, Page 273: \"Rome the seat of Antichrist will be consumed with fire, at the coming of Christ, or when the period of her apostacy is expired, in 1260 years from the rise of Antichrist.\" Page 275: \"...present Rome, when by an eruption of fire the mountainous soil, being undermined, will fall into an abyss, and be covered with the sea*</ref>\n\n{{quote|text= ''\"Antichrist will retain some part of his dominion over the nations till about the year 2016.\" \"And when the 1260 years are expired, Rome itself, with all its magnificence, will be absorbed in a lake of fire, sink into the sea, and rise no more at all for ever*.\"<ref>Rev. David Simpson \"A Plea for Religion and the Sacred Writings\" London: W. Baynes, and Paternoster-Row. (1808) 5th Edition, pages 131 and 133.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1870 the newly formed [[Kingdom of Italy]] annexed the remaining [[Papal States]], depriving the Popes of any temporal rule for the next 59 years. Unaware that Papal rule would be restored, (albeit on a greatly diminished scale) in 1929 as head of the [[Vatican City]] state, the historicist view that the Papacy is the Antichrist and the associated timelines delineating his rule rapidly declined in popularity as one of the defining characteristics of the Antichrist (i.e. that he would also be a political temporal power at the time of the return of Jesus) were no longer met.\n\nEventually, the prediction was largely forgotten and no major Protestant denomination currently subscribes to this timeline.\n\nDespite the dramatic nature of a prediction of the end of the world, Newton may not have been referring to the 2060 date as a destructive act resulting in the annihilation of the earth and its inhabitants, but rather one in which he believed the world was to be replaced with a new one based upon a transition to an era of divinely inspired peace. In Christian theology, this concept is often referred to as The [[Second Coming]] of [[Jesus Christ]] and the establishment of [[Paradise]] by The [[Kingdom of God]] on Earth.<ref name=Snobelen/>\n\n==Other beliefs==\n{{Main|Isaac Newton's occult studies}}\n[[File:Isaac Newton grave in Westminster Abbey.jpg|thumb|upright|Newton's grave in [[Westminster Abbey]]]]\n[[Henry More]]'s belief in the universe and rejection of [[Cartesian dualism]] may have influenced Newton's religious ideas.  Later works\u2014''The Chronology of Ancient Kingdoms Amended'' (1728) and ''Observations Upon the Prophecies of Daniel and the Apocalypse of St. John'' (1733)\u2014were published after his death.<ref name=\"Westfall\">{{cite book|last=Westfall|first=Richard S.|title=Science and Religion in Seventeenth-Century England|year=1973| publisher=U of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-06190-7|origyear=1964}}</ref>\n\nNewton and [[Robert Boyle|Boyle]]'s mechanical philosophy was promoted by rationalist pamphleteers as a viable alternative to the pantheists and enthusiasts, and was accepted hesitantly by orthodox clergy as well as dissident preachers like the latitudinarians.<ref name=\"jacob\" /> The clarity and simplicity of science was seen as a way in which to combat the emotional and mystical superlatives of superstitious enthusiasm, as well as the threat of atheism.<ref name=\"jacob\" />\n\nThe attacks made against pre-[[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] [[magical thinking]], and the [[mystical]] elements of [[Christianity]], were given their foundation with Boyle's mechanical conception of the universe.  Newton gave Boyle's ideas their completion through [[mathematical proof]]s, and more importantly was very successful in popularizing them.<ref name=\"Westfall\" /> Newton refashioned the world governed by an interventionist God into a world crafted by a God that designs along rational and universal principles.<ref>Fitzpatrick, Martin. ed. Knud Haakonssen. \"The Enlightenment, politics and providence: some Scottish and English comparisons.\" Enlightenment and Religion: Rational Dissent in eighteenth-century Britain. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge: 1996. p64.</ref> These principles were available for all people to discover, allowed man to pursue his own aims fruitfully in this life, not the next, and to perfect himself with his own rational powers.<ref>Frankel, Charles. The Faith of Reason: The Idea of Progress in the French Enlightenment. King's Crown Press, New York: 1948. p1.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nHis first writing on the subject of religion was ''Introductio. Continens Apocalypseos rationem generalem'' (''Introduction. Containing an explanation of the Apocalypse''), which has an unnumbered leaf between folios 1 and 2 with the subheading ''De prophetia prima'',<ref>The Newton Project, [http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/catalogue/record/THEM00046 THEM00046], retrieved 20 January 2014</ref> written in Latin some time prior to 1670. Written subsequently in English was ''Notes on early Church history and the moral superiority of the 'barbarians' to the Romans''. His last writing, published in 1737 with the miscellaneous works of John Greaves, was entitled ''A Dissertation upon the Sacred Cubit of the Jews and the Cubits of the several Nations''.<ref name=\"Iliffe\"/>\nNewton did not publish any of his works of biblical study during his lifetime.<ref name=\"Iliffe & Mandelbrote \"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=James E. Force|author2=Richard Henry Popkin|title=Essays on the Context, Nature, and Influence of Isaac Newton's Theology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=modLIHCBCIoC&pg=PA103|year=1990|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-0-7923-0583-5|page=103}}</ref> All of Newton's writings on corruption in biblical scripture and the church took place after the late 1670s and prior to the middle of 1690.<ref name=\"Iliffe & Mandelbrote \"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|Isaac Newton}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* [[Classical mechanics]]\n* [[Clockwork universe theory]]\n* [[Religious and philosophical views of Albert Einstein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eamon Duffy, \"Far from the Tree\" (review of Rob Iliffe, ''Priest of Nature: the Religious Worlds of Isaac Newton'', Oxford, Oxford University Press, 2017, vol. LXV, no. 4 (8 March 2018), pp.&nbsp;28\u201329.\n* Iliffe, Rob. ''Priest of Nature: The Religious Worlds of Isaac Newton''. Oxford University Press: 2017, 536 pp. [http://www.h-net.msu.edu/reviews/showrev.php?id=50285 online review]\n* Joalland, Michael. \"Isaac Newton Reads the King James Version: The Marginal Notes and Reading Marks of a Natural Philosopher\". ''Papers of the Bibliographical Society of America'', vol. 113, no. 3 (2019): 297\u2013339 (https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/704518?journalCode=pbsa)\n* Manuel, Frank. E. ''The Religion of Isaac Newton''. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1974.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Isaac Newton}}\n* [http://www.isaac-newton.org/ Isaac Newton Theology, Prophecy, Science and Religion]&nbsp;\u2013 writings on Newton by [[Stephen Snobelen]]\n* [http://web.nli.org.il/sites/NLI/English/collections/Humanities/Pages/newton.aspx The Newton Manuscripts at the National Library of Israel]&nbsp;\u2013 the collection of all his religious writings\n\n{{-}}\n{{Isaac Newton}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isaac Newton's Religious Views}}\n[[Category:Religious views by individual|Newton, Isaac]]\n[[Category:Isaac Newton|Religious Views]]\n[[Category:Nontrinitarianism]]\n[[Category:Criticism of atheism]]\n[[Category:Criticism of religion]]\n[[Category:Apocalypticism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg|thumb|Sir Isaac Newton at 46 in [[Godfrey Kneller]]'s 1689 portrait.]]\n{{Isaac Newton sidebar}}\n\n[[Isaac Newton]] (4 January 1643 \u2013 31 March 1727)<ref name=\"Christianson\">{{cite book |first=Gale E. |last=Christianson | url =https://archive.org/details/isaacnewtonscie00chri |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/isaacnewtonscie00chri/page/74 74] | title =  Isaac Newton and the scientific revolution | publisher = \u2013 155 pages Oxford portraits in science Oxford University Press|date= 19 September 1996| accessdate =  28 January 2012|isbn=0-19-509224-4}}</ref> was considered an insightful and erudite theologian by his contemporaries.<ref>{{citation|jstor=2708258|title=Isaac Newton on Science and Religion|journal=Journal of the History of Ideas|volume=31|issue=4|pages=521\u2013542|last1=Austin|first1=William H.|year=1970|doi=10.2307/2708258}}</ref><ref name=\"Iliffe & Mandelbrote \">[ENGLISH & LATIN] {{cite web | url =http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=73 | title =The Newton Project ''Newton's Views on the Corruptions of Scripture and the Church''  | accessdate = 28 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Iliffe\">[http://www.sussex.ac.uk/profiles/200167 Professor Rob Iliffe] (AHRC Newton Papers Project)  THE NEWTON PROJECT \u2013 ''Newton's Religious Writings''  [ENGLISH & LATIN] {{cite book | url =http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=44| title =  prism.php44 | publisher = University of Sussex| accessdate = 28 January 2012}}</ref> He wrote many works that would now be classified as [[Isaac Newton's occult studies|occult studies]] and [[religious tracts]] dealing with the [[Biblical literalism|literal interpretation of the Bible]].<ref name=newtonproject>{{cite web| title = Newton's Views on Prophecy  | publisher = The Newton Project  | date = 5 April 2007  | url = http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=74  | accessdate = 15 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nNewton's conception of the physical world provided a stable model of the natural world that would reinforce stability and harmony in the civic world. <!--The [[law of gravity]] became Newton's best-known discovery, but--> Newton saw a [[monotheistic God]] as the masterful creator whose existence could not be denied in the face of the grandeur of all creation.<ref name=\"Principia, Book III 1953\">Principia, Book III; cited in; Newton's Philosophy of Nature: Selections from his writings, p. 42, ed. H.S. Thayer, Hafner Library of Classics, NY, 1953.</ref><ref>A Short Scheme of the True Religion, manuscript quoted in Memoirs of the Life, Writings and Discoveries of Sir Isaac Newton by Sir David Brewster, Edinburgh, 1850; cited in; ibid, p. 65.</ref> Although born into an [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] family, by his thirties Newton held a [[Christian faith]] that, had it been made public, would not have been considered orthodox by mainstream [[Christianity]],<ref name=\"Newton - 1\">[[Richard S. Westfall]] \u2013 [[Indiana University]] {{cite book | url =http://galileo.rice.edu/Catalog/NewFiles/newton.html   | title = The Galileo Project   | publisher = ([[Rice University]]) | accessdate = 5 July 2008}}</ref> with one modern historian labeling him a [[heresy|heretic]].<ref name=\"heretic\">{{cite journal |last=Snobelen |first=Stephen D. |authorlink=Stephen Snobelen |title=Isaac Newton, heretic : the strategies of a Nicodemite |journal=British Journal for the History of Science |volume=32 |pages=381\u2013419 |year=1999 |url=http://www.toriah.org/articles/snobelen-1999-1.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908043029/http://www.toriah.org/articles/snobelen-1999-1.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2014 |doi=10.1017/S0007087499003751 |issue=4 }}</ref>\n\n==Christian orthodoxy==\nNewton was born into an Anglican family three months after the death of his father, a prosperous farmer also named Isaac Newton. When Newton was three, his mother married the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)#Anglican churches|rector]] of the neighbouring parish of [[North Witham]] and went to live with her new husband, the Reverend Barnabus Smith, leaving her son in the care of his maternal grandmother, Margery Ayscough.<ref>{{cite book\n|title=Illustrations of the literary history of the eighteenth century: Consisting of authentic memoirs and original letters of eminent persons; and intended as a sequel to the Literary anecdotes, Volume 4 |first1=John Bowyer |last1=Nichols |publisher=Nichols, Son, and Bentley |year=1822 |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_pBEUAAAAQAAJ/page/n56 32] |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_pBEUAAAAQAAJ}}</ref> Isaac apparently hated his step-father, and had nothing to do with Smith during his childhood.<ref name=\"Newton - 1\"/> His maternal uncle, the rector serving the parish of [[Burton Coggles]],<ref>{{cite book|author=C. D. Broad|authorlink=C. D. Broad|title=Ethics and the History of Philosophy: Selected Essays|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mccz8hwkfvgC&pg=PA3|volume=Volume 1|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-22530-4|page=3}}</ref> was involved to some extent in the care of Isaac.\n\nIn 1667 Newton became a Fellow of [[Trinity College, Cambridge]],<ref>[[Cambridge University]] [https://archive.is/20120715113444/http://venn.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/search.pl?sur=Newton&suro=c&fir=Isaac&firo=c&cit=&cito=c&c=all&tex=&sye=&eye=&col=all&maxcount=50 Alumni Database] Retrieved 29 January 2012</ref> making necessary his commitment to taking [[Holy Orders]] within seven years of completing his [[Master of Arts|MA]], which he did the following year. He was also required to take a vow of celibacy and recognize the [[Thirty-Nine Articles]] of the Church of England.<ref name=\"Iliffe-2\">Professor Rob Iliffe (AHRC Newton Papers Project) THE NEWTON PROJECT {{cite book | url =http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/prism.php?id=15| title =  prism.php15 | publisher = University of Sussex| accessdate = 7 February 2012}}</ref> Newton considered ceasing his studies prior to completion in order to avoid the ordination made necessary by law of [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]].<ref name=\"Cambridge \">[[Cambridge University Library]] {{cite book | url =https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:8bhDeW5cfrYJ:www.lib.cam.ac.uk/exhibitions/Footprints_of_the_Lion/scholar.pdf+Newton+on+Maimonides&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgKghLb5qt9p3T_uupTyiiQnW__s-6Bx0xOZrHx4H3wChat3we54G4ciNJ2I7D_O69Rl_w7B12E_R0-VjP1tUOrJlF88_maweWYap1SQeK5bOj5e9jipxm9mSbrPhnRiDch9mlK&sig=AHIEtbSJEIrnGcjqkfWUiIfmCafcyyQJfA |title= .ac| accessdate =  29 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\" Christianson  \"/> He was eventually successful in avoiding the statute, assisted in this by the efforts of [[Isaac Barrow]], as in 1676 the then [[Secretary of State for the Northern Department]], [[Joseph Williamson (English politician)|Joseph Williamson]], changed the relevant statute of Trinity College to provide dispensation from this duty.<ref name=\"Iliffe-2\"/> After taking advantage of that, Newton embarked on an investigative study of the early history of the Church, which developed, during the 1680s, into inquiries about the origins of religion. At around the same time, he developed a scientific view on motion and matter.<ref name=\"Cambridge\"/> Of ''[[Philosophi\u00e6 Naturalis Principia Mathematica]]'' he stated:<ref>S.D.Snobelen ([[University of King's College]]) \u2013 ''To Discourse of God : Isaac Newton's Heterdox Theology and Natural Philosophy'' [https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:O3EkKGIo9uwJ:www.isaac-newton.org/pdf/Snobelen%2520Newton%2520To%2520discourse%2520of%2520God%25202004.pdf+Newton+at+Cambridge+theology&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShNj3l0Oaf79xt3TGwPIh534c9N1-zNZsRLhkIn1vnWZ7M9mCXjGnqIIGwz4_Zb1WYv_DG_r12lg4-KouEDVIiiACxJCnyu88V9ZTQ_w8bORXoBVZsT9RGDH_gMH5gPUxY7BZFm&sig=AHIEtbSzLx1OAvnyKCX1UZB7GlgCmzA63Q Nova Scotia] Retrieved 29 January 2012</ref>\n{{quote|When I wrote my treatise about our Systeme I had an eye upon such Principles as might work with considering men for the beliefe of a Deity and nothing can rejoyce me more than to find it useful for that purpose.}}\n\n\nAccording to most scholars, Newton was [[Arianism|Arian]], not holding to [[Trinity|Trinitarianism]].<ref name=\"heretic\"/><ref name=dulles/><ref name=\"neveratrest\">Richard Westfall, '' Never at Rest: A Biography of Isaac Newton,'' (1980) pp. 103, 25.</ref> As well as being [[Nontrinitarianism|antitrinitarian]], Newton allegedly rejected the orthodox doctrines of the [[Immortality of the soul|immortal soul]],<ref name=\"heretic\"/> a personal [[devil]] and literal [[demon]]s.<ref name=\"heretic\"/> Although he was not a [[Socinianism|Socinian]] he shared many similar beliefs with them.<ref name=\"heretic\"/> A manuscript he sent to [[John Locke]] in which he disputed the existence of the [[Trinity]] was never published. In a minority view, T.C. Pfizenmaier argued Newton was neither \"orthodox\" nor an Arian,<ref>Pfizenmaier, T.C, \"The Trinitarian Theology of Dr. Samuel Clarke\" (1675\u20131729)</ref> but that, rather, Newton believed both of these groups had wandered into metaphysical speculation.<ref name=\"arian?\">Pfizenmaier, T.C., \"Was Isaac Newton an Arian?\" Journal of the History of Ideas 68(1):57\u201380, 1997.</ref> Pfizenmaier also argued that Newton held closer to the [[Semi-Arian]] view of the Trinity that [[Jesus Christ]] was of a \"similar substance\" ([[homoiousios]]) from the Father rather than the orthodox view that Jesus Christ is of the \"same substance\" of the Father ([[homoousios]]) as endorsed by modern [[Eastern Orthodox]], [[Roman Catholics]] and [[Protestant]]s.<ref name=\"arian?\"/> [[Stephen Snobelen|S. D. Snobelen]] has also argued against this from manuscripts produced late in Newton's life which demonstrate Newton rejected the Eastern view of the Trinity.<ref name=\"heretic\"/>\n\nNewton refused [[Viaticum]] before his death.<ref name=\"Newton - 1\"/>\n\n==God as masterful creator==\nNewton saw God as the masterful creator whose existence could not be denied in the face of the grandeur of all creation.<ref>Webb, R.K. ed. Knud Haakonssen. \"The emergence of Rational Dissent.\" Enlightenment and Religion: Rational Dissent in eighteenth-century Britain. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge: 1996. p19.</ref> Nevertheless, he rejected [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]]'s thesis that God would necessarily make a perfect world which requires no intervention from the creator. In Query 31 of the ''Opticks'', Newton simultaneously made an argument from design and for the necessity of intervention:\n{{quote| For while comets move in very eccentric orbs in all manner of positions, blind fate could never make all the planets move one and the same way in orbs concentric, some inconsiderable irregularities excepted which may have arisen from the mutual actions of comets and planets on one another, and which will be apt to increase, till this system wants a reformation.<ref>Newton, 1706 ''Opticks'' (2nd Edition), quoted in H. G. Alexander 1956 (ed): ''The Leibniz-Clarke correspondence'', University of Manchester Press.</ref>}}\nThis passage prompted an attack by Leibniz in a letter to his friend [[Caroline of Ansbach]]:\n{{quote|Sir Isaac Newton and his followers have also a very odd opinion concerning the work of God. According to their doctrine, God Almighty wants to wind up his watch from time to time: otherwise it would cease to move. He had not, it seems, sufficient foresight to make it a perpetual motion.<ref>Leibniz, first letter, in Alexander 1956, p. 11</ref>}}\nLeibniz's letter initiated the [[Leibniz-Clarke correspondence]], ostensibly with Newton's friend and disciple [[Samuel Clarke]], although as Caroline wrote, Clarke's letters \"are not written without the advice of the Chev. Newton\".<ref>Caroline to Leibniz, 10 January 1716, quoted in Alexander 1956, p. 193. (Chev. = Chevalier i.e. Knight.)</ref>\nClarke complained that Leibniz's concept of God as a \"supra-mundane intelligence\" who set up a \"pre-established harmony\" was only a step from atheism: \"And as those men, who pretend that in an earthly government things may go on perfectly well without the king himself ordering or disposing of any thing, may reasonably be suspected that they would like very well to set the king aside: so, whosoever contends, that the beings of the world can go on without the continual direction of God...his doctrine does in effect tend to exclude God out of the world\".<ref>Clarke, first reply, in Alexander 1956 p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn addition to stepping in to re-form the solar system, Newton invoked God's active intervention to prevent the stars falling in on each other, and perhaps in preventing the amount of motion in the universe from decaying due to viscosity and friction.<ref>H.W. Alexander 1956, p. xvii</ref> In private correspondence Newton sometimes hinted that the force of Gravity was due to an immaterial influence:\n{{quote|Tis inconceivable that inanimate brute matter should (without the mediation of something else which is not material) operate upon & affect other matter without mutual contact.<ref>Newton to Bentley, 25 February 1693</ref>}}\nLeibniz jibed that such an immaterial influence would be a continual miracle; this was another strand of his debate with Clarke.\n\nNewton's view has been considered to be close to [[deism]] and several biographers and scholars labeled him as a deist who is strongly influenced by Christianity.<ref>{{cite book|title=Essays on the Context, Nature, and Influence of Isaac Newton's Theology|year=1990|publisher=Springer|isbn=9780792305835|first=James E.|last= Force|first2= Richard Henry |last2=Popkin|editor-first=James E. |editor-last=Force|editor2-first= Richard Henry |editor2-last=Popkin|page=53|quote=Newton has often been identified as a deist. ...In the 19th century, William Blake seems to have put Newton into the deistic camp. Scholars in the 20th-century have often continued to view Newton as a deist. Gerald R. Cragg views Newton as a kind of proto-deist and, as evidence, points to Newton's belief in a true, original, monotheistic religion first discovered in ancient times by natural reason. This position, in Cragg's view, leads to the elimination of the Christian revelation as neither necessary nor sufficient for human knowledge of God. This agenda is indeed the key point, as Leland describes above, of the deistic program which seeks to \"set aside\" revelatory religious texts. Cragg writes that, \"In effect, Newton ignored the claims of revelation and pointed in a direction which many eighteenth-century thinkers would willingly follow.\" John Redwood has also recently linked anti-Trinitarian theology with both \"Newtonianism\" and \"deism.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Innermost Kernel: Depth Psychology and Quantum Physics. Wolfgang Pauli's Dialogue with C.G. Jung|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783540208563|pages=181\u2013182|first=Suzanne |last=Gieser|quote=Newton seems to have been closer to the deists in his conception of God and had no time for the doctrine of the Trinity. The deists did not recognize the divine nature of Christ. According to Fierz, Newton's conception of God permeated his entire scientific work: God's universality and eternity express themselves in the dominion of the laws of nature. Time and space are regarded as the 'organs' of God. All is contained and moves in God but without having any effect on God himself. Thus space and time become metaphysical entities, superordinate existences that are not associated with any interaction, activity or observation on man's part.|date=14 February 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Classical Mechanics: Transformations, Flows, Integrable and Chaotic Dynamics|year=1997|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521578820|first=Joseph L. |last=McCauley|page=3|quote=Newton (1642\u20131727), as a seventeenth century nonChristian Deist, would have been susceptible to an accusation of heresy by either the Anglican Church or the Puritans.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Philosophical problems of modern physics|year=1982|publisher=Reidel|editor=Hans S. Plendl|page=361|quote=Newton expressed the same conception of the nature of atoms in his deistic view of the Universe.}}</ref> However, he differed from strict adherents of deism in that he invoked God as a special physical cause to keep the planets in orbits.<ref name=dulles>Avery Cardinal Dulles. [http://www.firstthings.com/article.php3?id_article=143 The Deist Minimum]. 2005.</ref> He warned against using the [[law of gravity]] to view the universe as a mere machine, like a great clock. He said:\n\n{{quote|This most beautiful system of the sun, planets, and comets, could only proceed from the counsel and dominion of an intelligent Being. [...] This Being governs all things, not as the soul of the world, but as Lord over all; and on account of his dominion he is wont to be called \"Lord God\" \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03c9\u03c1 [pantokrat\u014dr], or \"Universal Ruler\". [...] The Supreme God is a Being eternal, infinite, [and] absolutely perfect.<ref name=\"Principia, Book III 1953\"/>}}\n\n{{quote|Opposition to godliness is atheism in profession and idolatry in practice. Atheism is so senseless and odious to mankind that it never had many professors.<ref>Brewster, Sir David. ''A Short Scheme of the True Religion, manuscript quoted in Memoirs of the Life, Writings and Discoveries of Sir Isaac Newton'' Edinburgh, 1850.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/view/texts/normalized/THEM00007|title=A short Schem of the true Religion|website=The Newton Project|publisher=[[University of Sussex]]|location=East Sussex|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GRWuKYu6?url=http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/view/texts/normalized/THEM00007|archivedate=7 May 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nOn the other hand, [[latitudinarian]] and Newtonian ideas taken too far resulted in the millenarians, a religious faction dedicated to the concept of a mechanical universe, but finding in it the same enthusiasm and mysticism that the Enlightenment had fought so hard to extinguish.<ref name=\"jacob\">Jacob, Margaret C. The Newtonians and the English Revolution: 1689\u20131720.</ref> Newton himself may have had some interest in [[millenarianism]] as he wrote about both the [[Book of Daniel]] and the [[Book of Revelation]] in his [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16878/16878-h/16878-h.htm Observations Upon the Prophecies].\n\nNewton's conception of the physical world provided a stable model of the natural world that would reinforce stability and harmony in the civic world.<ref name=\"jacob\" />\n\n==The Bible==\n\nNewton spent a great deal of time trying to discover [[Bible code|hidden messages within the Bible]].  After 1690, Newton wrote a number of [[religious tracts]] dealing with the literal interpretation of the [[Bible]]. In a manuscript Newton wrote in 1704 he describes his attempts to extract scientific information from the Bible. He estimated that the world would end no earlier than 2060. In predicting this he said \"This I mention not to assert when the time of the end shall be, but to put a stop to the rash conjectures of fanciful men who are frequently predicting the time of the end, and by doing so bring the sacred prophesies into discredit as often as their predictions fail.\"<ref name=\"paper\">{{cite news |title=Papers Show Isaac Newton's Religious Side, Predict Date of Apocalypse |agency=Associated Press |date=19 June 2007 |url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20070619/28049_Papers_Show_Isaac_Newton%27s_Religious_Side%2C_Predict_Date_of_Apocalypse.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070629231937/http://www.christianpost.com/article/20070619/28049_Papers_Show_Isaac_Newton's_Religious_Side,_Predict_Date_of_Apocalypse.htm |archivedate=29 June 2007 |accessdate=17 May 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Library of Trinity College, Cambridge, holds in its collections Newton's personal copy of the King James Version, which exhibits numerous marginal notes in his hand as well as about 500 reader's marks pointing to passages of particular interest to him. A note is attached to the Bible indicating that it \"was given by Sir Isaac Newton in his last illness to the woman who nursed him\". The book was eventually bequeathed to the Library in 1878. The places Newton marked or annotated in his Bible bear witness to his investigations into theology, chronology, alchemy, and natural philosophy; and some of these actually relate to passages of the ''General Scholium'' to the second edition of the ''Principia''. Some other passages he marked offer glimpses of his devotional practices and reveal distinct tensions in his personality. Newton's Bible appears to have been first and foremost a customized reference tool in the hands of a biblical scholar and critic.<ref>Joalland, Michael. \"Isaac Newton Reads the King James Version: The Marginal Notes and Reading Marks of a Natural Philosopher\". ''Papers of the Bibliographical Society of America'', vol. 113, no. 3 (2019): 297\u2013339 (https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/704518?journalCode=pbsa)</ref>\n\n===Prophecy===\nNewton relied upon the existing Scripture for prophecy, believing his interpretations would set the record straight in the face of what he considered to be, \"so little understood\".<ref>{{cite web  | last = Newton  | first = Isaac  | title = The First Book Concerning the Language of the Prophets  | publisher = The Newton Project  | date = 5 April 2007  | url = http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/texts/viewtext.php?id=THEM00005&mode=normalized  | accessdate = 15 August 2007  | url-status = dead  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108210637/http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/texts/viewtext.php?id=THEM00005&mode=normalized  | archivedate = 8 November 2007  | df = dmy-all  }}</ref> Though he would never write a cohesive body of work on Prophecy, Newton's beliefs would lead him to write several treatises on the subject, including an unpublished guide for prophetic interpretation titled ''Rules for interpreting the words & language in Scripture''. In this manuscript he details the necessary requirements for what he considered to be the proper interpretation of the Bible.\n\n===End of The World vs Start of The Millennial Kingdom===\n\nIn his posthumously-published ''Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel, and the Apocalypse of St. John'', Newton expressed his belief that Bible prophecy would not be understood \"until the time of the end\", and that even then \"none of the wicked shall understand\". Referring to that as a future time (\"the last age, the age of opening these things, be now approaching\"), Newton also anticipated \"the general preaching of the Gospel be approaching\" and \"the Gospel must first be preached in all nations before the great tribulation, and end of the world\".<ref>''Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel, and the Apocalypse of St. John'' by Sir Isaac Newton, 1733, J. DARBY and T. BROWNE, [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16878/16878-h/16878-h.htm#NtpJohI_41 Online]</ref>\n\nOver the years, a large amount of media attention and public interest has circulated regarding largely unknown and unpublished documents, evidently written by Isaac Newton, that indicate he believed the world could end in 2060. While Newton also had many other possible dates (e.g. 2034),<ref name=Snobelen>{{cite web\n  | last = Snobelen  | first = Stephen D  | title = Statement on the date 2060  | url = http://www.isaac-newton.org/update.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015054011/http://www.isaac-newton.org/update.html  |archivedate=15 October 2013| accessdate = 4 February 2014}}</ref> he did not believe that the end of the world would take place specifically in 2060.<ref>[http://cjhistory.synergiesprairies.ca/cjhistory/index.php/cjhistory/article/view/8886 \"A time and times and the dividing of times\": Isaac Newton, the Apocalypse and 2060 AD Snobelen, S Can J Hist (2003) vol 38] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221074953/http://cjhistory.synergiesprairies.ca/cjhistory/index.php/cjhistory/article/view/8886 |date=21 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nLike most Protestant theologians of his time, Newton believed that the Papal Office (and not any one particular Pope) was the fulfillment of the Biblical predictions about [[Antichrist]], whose rule was predicted to last for 1,260 years. They applied the [[day-year principle]] (in which a day represents a year in prophecy) to certain key verses in the books of Daniel<ref>the \"time, times and half a time\" of Daniel 7:25 and 12:7</ref> and Revelation<ref>the \"42 months\" of Revelation 11:2 and 13:5 equals the \"1260 days\" of Revelation 11:3 and 12:6</ref> (also known as the Apocalypse), and looked for significant dates in the Papacy's rise to power to begin this timeline. Newton's calculation ending in 2060 is based on the 1,260-year timeline commencing in 800 AD when [[Charlemagne]] became the first Holy Roman Emperor and reconfirmed the earlier (756 AD) [[Donation of Pepin]] to the Papacy.<ref name=\"paper\"/>\n\n=== 2016 vs 2060 ===\n\nHowever, between the time he wrote his 2060 prediction (about 1704) until his death in 1727 Newton conversed, both first hand and by correspondence, with other famous theologians of his time. Those contemporaries who knew him during the remaining 23 years of his life appear to be in agreement that Newton, and the \"best interpreters\" including [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards]], [[Robert Fleming the younger|Robert Fleming]], [[Moses Lowman]], [[Phillip Doddridge]], and Bishop [[Thomas Newton]], were eventually \"pretty well agreed\" that the 1,260-year timeline should be calculated from the year 756 AD.<ref>Jonathan Edwards \u201dHistory of Redemption\" New York: T. and J. Swords (1793) page 431: \"The Beginning of the reign of Antichrist.] The best interpreters (as Mr. Fleming, Sir I. Newton, Mr. Lowman, Dr. Doddridge, Bp. Newton, and Mr. Reader) are pretty well agreed that this reign is to be dated from about A. D. 756, when the Pope began to be a temporal power, (that is, in prophetic language, a beast) by assuming temporal dominion; 1260 years from this period will bring us to about A. D. 2000, and about the 6000th year of the world, which agrees with a tradition at least as ancient as the epistle ascribed to the apostle Barnabas (f 15.] which says, that \" in six thousand years shall all things be accomplished.\"</ref>\n\nF.A. Cox also confirmed that this was the view of Newton and others, including himself:\n\n{{bquote | ''\"The author adopts the hypothesis of Fleming, Sir Isaac Newton, and Lowman, that the 1260 years commenced in A.d. 756; and consequently that the millennium will not begin till the year 2016\".''<ref>Rev. F.A. Cox \"Outlines of Lectures on the Book of Daniel\" London: Westley and Davis (1833) 2nd Edition Page 152</ref>}}\n\n[[Thomas Williams (1755\u20131839)|Thomas Williams]] stated that this timeline had become the predominant view among the leading Protestant theologians of his time:\n\n{{bquote | ''\"Mr. Lowman, though an earlier commentator, is (we believe) far more generally followed ; and he commences the 1260 days from about 756, when, by aid of Pepin, King of France, the Pope obtained considerable temporalities. This carries on the reign of Popery to 2016, or sixteen years into the commencement of the Millennium, as it is generally reckoned\".''<ref>Thomas Williams \"The Cottage Bible and family expositor\" Hartford: D.F. Robinson and H. F. Sumner (1837) Vol. 2-page 1417</ref>}}\n \nIn April of 756 AD, [[Pepin the Short|Pepin]], King of France, accompanied by [[Pope Stephen II]] entered northern Italy, forcing the Lombard King [[Aistulf]] to lift his siege of Rome, and return to [[Pavia]]. Following Aistulf's capitulation, Pepin gave the newly conquered territories to the Papacy by means of the [[Donation of Pepin]], thereby elevating the Pope from being a subject of the [[Byzantine Empire]] to [[head of state]], with [[temporal power (papal)|temporal power]] over the newly constituted [[Papal States]].\n\nThe end of the timeline is based on Daniel 8:25 which reads ''\"...but he shall be broken without hand\"'' and is understood to mean that the end of the Papacy will not be caused by any human action.<ref>Bishop Thomas Newton \"DISSERTATIONS ON THE PROPHECIES\" London: J.F. and C. Rivington (1789) 8th Edition Page 327: \"As the stone in Nebuchadnezzar's dream was cut out of the mountain without hands, that is not by human, but by supernatural means; so the little horn shall be broken without hand, not die the common death, not fall by the hand of men, but perish by a stroke from heaven.\"</ref> Volcanic activity is described as the means by which Rome will be overthrown.<ref>East Apthorp, D.D. \"Discourses on Prophecy\" (1786) Discourse XI, Page 273: \"Rome the seat of Antichrist will be consumed with fire, at the coming of Christ, or when the period of her apostacy is expired, in 1260 years from the rise of Antichrist.\" Page 275: \"...present Rome, when by an eruption of fire the mountainous soil, being undermined, will fall into an abyss, and be covered with the sea*</ref>\n\n{{quote|text= ''\"Antichrist will retain some part of his dominion over the nations till about the year 2016.\" \"And when the 1260 years are expired, Rome itself, with all its magnificence, will be absorbed in a lake of fire, sink into the sea, and rise no more at all for ever*.\"<ref>Rev. David Simpson \"A Plea for Religion and the Sacred Writings\" London: W. Baynes, and Paternoster-Row. (1808) 5th Edition, pages 131 and 133.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1870 the newly formed [[Kingdom of Italy]] annexed the remaining [[Papal States]], depriving the Popes of any temporal rule for the next 59 years. Unaware that Papal rule would be restored, (albeit on a greatly diminished scale) in 1929 as head of the [[Vatican City]] state, the historicist view that the Papacy is the Antichrist and the associated timelines delineating his rule rapidly declined in popularity as one of the defining characteristics of the Antichrist (i.e. that he would also be a political temporal power at the time of the return of Jesus) were no longer met.\n\nEventually, the prediction was largely forgotten and no major Protestant denomination currently subscribes to this timeline.\n\nDespite the dramatic nature of a prediction of the end of the world, Newton may not have been referring to the 2060 date as a destructive act resulting in the annihilation of the earth and its inhabitants, but rather one in which he believed the world was to be replaced with a new one based upon a transition to an era of divinely inspired peace. In Christian theology, this concept is often referred to as The [[Second Coming]] of [[Jesus Christ]] and the establishment of [[Paradise]] by The [[Kingdom of God]] on Earth.<ref name=Snobelen/>\n\n==Other beliefs==\n{{Main|Isaac Newton's occult studies}}\n[[File:Isaac Newton grave in Westminster Abbey.jpg|thumb|upright|Newton's grave in [[Westminster Abbey]]]]\n[[Henry More]]'s belief in the universe and rejection of [[Cartesian dualism]] may have influenced Newton's religious ideas.  Later works\u2014''The Chronology of Ancient Kingdoms Amended'' (1728) and ''Observations Upon the Prophecies of Daniel and the Apocalypse of St. John'' (1733)\u2014were published after his death.<ref name=\"Westfall\">{{cite book|last=Westfall|first=Richard S.|title=Science and Religion in Seventeenth-Century England|year=1973| publisher=U of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-06190-7|origyear=1964}}</ref>\n\nNewton and [[Robert Boyle|Boyle]]'s mechanical philosophy was promoted by rationalist pamphleteers as a viable alternative to the pantheists and enthusiasts, and was accepted hesitantly by orthodox clergy as well as dissident preachers like the latitudinarians.<ref name=\"jacob\" /> The clarity and simplicity of science was seen as a way in which to combat the emotional and mystical superlatives of superstitious enthusiasm, as well as the threat of atheism.<ref name=\"jacob\" />\n\nThe attacks made against pre-[[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] [[magical thinking]], and the [[mystical]] elements of [[Christianity]], were given their foundation with Boyle's mechanical conception of the universe.  Newton gave Boyle's ideas their completion through [[mathematical proof]]s, and more importantly was very successful in popularizing them.<ref name=\"Westfall\" /> Newton refashioned the world governed by an interventionist God into a world crafted by a God that designs along rational and universal principles.<ref>Fitzpatrick, Martin. ed. Knud Haakonssen. \"The Enlightenment, politics and providence: some Scottish and English comparisons.\" Enlightenment and Religion: Rational Dissent in eighteenth-century Britain. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge: 1996. p64.</ref> These principles were available for all people to discover, allowed man to pursue his own aims fruitfully in this life, not the next, and to perfect himself with his own rational powers.<ref>Frankel, Charles. The Faith of Reason: The Idea of Progress in the French Enlightenment. King's Crown Press, New York: 1948. p1.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nHis first writing on the subject of religion was ''Introductio. Continens Apocalypseos rationem generalem'' (''Introduction. Containing an explanation of the Apocalypse''), which has an unnumbered leaf between folios 1 and 2 with the subheading ''De prophetia prima'',<ref>The Newton Project, [http://www.newtonproject.sussex.ac.uk/catalogue/record/THEM00046 THEM00046], retrieved 20 January 2014</ref> written in Latin some time prior to 1670. Written subsequently in English was ''Notes on early Church history and the moral superiority of the 'barbarians' to the Romans''. His last writing, published in 1737 with the miscellaneous works of John Greaves, was entitled ''A Dissertation upon the Sacred Cubit of the Jews and the Cubits of the several Nations''.<ref name=\"Iliffe\"/>\nNewton did not publish any of his works of biblical study during his lifetime.<ref name=\"Iliffe & Mandelbrote \"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=James E. Force|author2=Richard Henry Popkin|title=Essays on the Context, Nature, and Influence of Isaac Newton's Theology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=modLIHCBCIoC&pg=PA103|year=1990|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-0-7923-0583-5|page=103}}</ref> All of Newton's writings on corruption in biblical scripture and the church took place after the late 1670s and prior to the middle of 1690.<ref name=\"Iliffe & Mandelbrote \"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|Isaac Newton}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* [[Classical mechanics]]\n* [[Clockwork universe theory]]\n* [[Religious and philosophical views of Albert Einstein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eamon Duffy, \"Far from the Tree\" (review of Rob Iliffe, ''Priest of Nature: the Religious Worlds of Isaac Newton'', Oxford, Oxford University Press, 2017, vol. LXV, no. 4 (8 March 2018), pp.&nbsp;28\u201329.\n* Iliffe, Rob. ''Priest of Nature: The Religious Worlds of Isaac Newton''. Oxford University Press: 2017, 536 pp. [http://www.h-net.msu.edu/reviews/showrev.php?id=50285 online review]\n* Joalland, Michael. \"Isaac Newton Reads the King James Version: The Marginal Notes and Reading Marks of a Natural Philosopher\". ''Papers of the Bibliographical Society of America'', vol. 113, no. 3 (2019): 297\u2013339 (https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/704518?journalCode=pbsa)\n* Manuel, Frank. E. ''The Religion of Isaac Newton''. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1974.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Isaac Newton}}\n* [http://www.isaac-newton.org/ Isaac Newton Theology, Prophecy, Science and Religion]&nbsp;\u2013 writings on Newton by [[Stephen Snobelen]]\n* [http://web.nli.org.il/sites/NLI/English/collections/Humanities/Pages/newton.aspx The Newton Manuscripts at the National Library of Israel]&nbsp;\u2013 the collection of all his religious writings\n\n{{-}}\n{{Isaac Newton}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isaac Newton's Religious Views}}\n[[Category:Religious views by individual|Newton, Isaac]]\n[[Category:Isaac Newton|Religious Views]]\n[[Category:Nontrinitarianism]]\n[[Category:Criticism of atheism]]\n[[Category:Criticism of religion]]\n[[Category:Apocalypticism]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "British spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religious_views_of_Isaac_Newton"}
{"title_page": "Ansel Elgort", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, singer and DJ|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ansel Elgort\n| image              = Ansel Elgort (35875410045).jpg\n| caption            = Elgort at the premiere of ''[[Baby Driver]]'' in 2017\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1994|3|14|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], U.S. <!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birthplace indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| education          = [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actor\n* singer\n*DJ\n}}\n| partner            = Violetta Komyshan <!--GIRLFRIENDS, MARRIAGE AND PAST PARTNERS!-->\n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n* [[Arthur Elgort]]\n* [[Grethe Barrett Holby]]\n}}\n| yearsactive        = 2012\u2013present\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| alias               = Ans\u00f8lo\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[soul music|soul]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n}}\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* [[Singing|Vocals]]\n* [[Disc jockey|DJ]]\n}}\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]] (2015\u2013present)\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Tom Staar]]\n* [[Too Many Zooz]]\n* [[Logic (musician)|Logic]]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ansel Elgort''' (born March 14, 1994)<ref name=twitref1>{{cite web |last=Elgort |first=Ansel |title=Ansel Elgort: \"I'm 19 today...that's my attempt at a birthday hat and blowing a noise maker...\" |publisher=Twitter |date=March 14, 2013 |url=https://www.twitter.com/AnselElgort/status/312203341721653248?p=v |accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=chic1>{{cite news |last=Markey |first=Judy |title=This Picture Is Worth A Thousand Puzzles|pages= |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=December 15, 1994 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB421F8A8885CD5&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=nyt1>{{cite news |last=Ward |first=Timothy Jack |title=Family Albums: A Pro's Take (With Tips) |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 14, 1997 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/14/garden/family-albums-a-pro-s-take-with-tips.html |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113044433/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/14/garden/family-albums-a-pro-s-take-with-tips.html |archivedate=November 13, 2013 |df= }}</ref> is an American actor, singer, dancer, and DJ (under the name '''Ans\u00f8lo''').<ref name=THR/><ref name=bb>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7832934/ansel-elgort-baby-driver-2017-cover-story |first=Rebecca |last=Milzoff |title=Ansel Elgort Breaks Out With 'Baby Driver' and a Frank Oce@n-Approved Singing Career: 'I'm Hopefully Going to Pull It All Off' |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 15, 2017 |accessdate=July 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616035559/http://www.billbored.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7832934/ansel-elgort-baby-driver-2017-cover-story |archivedate=June 16, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Born to photographer [[Arthur Elgort]] and stage producer [[Grethe Barrett Holby]], he began his acting career with a supporting role in the horror film ''[[Carrie (2013 film)|Carrie]]'' (2013).\n\nElgort gained wider recognition for starring as a teenage cancer patient in the romantic drama ''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]'' (2014) and for his role in ''[[The Divergent Series]]'' franchise. In 2017, he played the title character in [[Edgar Wright]]'s action thriller ''[[Baby Driver]]'', for which he received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]. As a singer, he has released the singles \"Thief\" (2017) and \"Supernova\" (2018).I love him\n\n==Early life==\nElgort was born in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]].<ref name=interviewmag1>{{cite magazine |last=Cole |first=Rachel T. |title=Film: Ansel Elgort |magazine=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |date=March 18, 2013 |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/ansel-elgort |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609091446/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/ansel-elgort |archivedate=June 9, 2013 |df= }}</ref> His parents are [[Arthur Elgort]], a fashion photographer who has worked extensively for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' for over 30 years,<ref>{{cite web |title=Look Back at Arthur Elgort's Most Stunning Fashion Photos |url=https://www.thecut.com/2015/01/revisit-arthur-elgorts-iconic-fashion-photos.html |first=Erica |last=Schwiegershausen |date=January 15, 2015 |publisher=New York Magazine's The Cut}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Photographer Arthur Elgort To Be Given the CFDA Board of Directors Award Tonight |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/photographer-arthur-elgort-to-be-given-the-cfda-board-of-directors-award |first=Mark |last=Holgate |date=June 6, 2011 |magazine=Vogue Magazine}}</ref> and [[Grethe Barrett Holby]], an opera director.<ref name=vog1>{{cite magazine |last=Schillinger |first=Liesl |title=Ansel Elgort Goes from High School to Off Broadway in Regrets |magazine=Vogue |date=March 28, 2012 |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/breaking-out-ansel-elgort-stars-in-regrets-off-broadway |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520213353/http://www.vogue.com/culture/article/breaking-out-ansel-elgort-stars-in-regrets-off-broadway/ |archivedate=May 20, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.papermag.com/at-home-with-the-elgort-family-1427378597.html|title=At Home With the Elgort Family|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|date=September 4, 2014|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=nytob2>{{cite news |title=Paid Notice: Deaths; HOLBY, AASE GRETHE |newspaper=The New York Times |date=February 1, 2012 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E03E7D8133AF932A35751C0A9649D8B63 |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923072333/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E03E7D8133AF932A35751C0A9649D8B63 |archivedate=September 23, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Elgort's father is of [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] descent,<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Remarkable Jewish Background of 'Baby Driver' Star Ansel Elgort |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/239789/the-remarkable-jewish-background-of-baby-driver-star-ansel-elgort |first=Jonathan |last=Zalman |date=July 3, 2017 |magazine=Tablet Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ansel Elgort's Star Rises With 'Divergent' Movie |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=291961138 |first=Robin |last=Young |date=March 20, 2014 |work=[[NPR]]}}</ref> and his mother is of [[Norwegian American|Norwegian]], [[English American|English]] and [[German American|German]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ansel Elgort: there's no fault with this star|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/ansel-elgort-there-s-no-fault-with-this-star-1.2017744|first=Donald|last=Clarke|date=November 28, 2014|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.instyle.com/news/ansel-elgorts-adorable-holiday-plans|title=Ansel Elgort's Adorable Holiday Plans Will Make You Want to Join His Family|last=Stern|first=Claire|date=November 18, 2015|work=[[InStyle]]|accessdate=May 6, 2018|quote=\"We have Norwegian roots, so we like to acknowledge that,\"}}</ref><ref name=divref1>{{cite web |date=February 24, 2014 |url=http://www.divergentlife.com/2014/02/new-ansel-elgort-live-stream-q-200k.html |title=Ansel Elgort's Live Stream |work=Divergent Society.net |quote=Quote stated at 22:05 in the interview.}}</ref>\n\nElgort's Norwegian maternal grandmother, Aase-Grethe,<ref>{{cite web|first=Alexandra|last=Macon|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/sophie-ansel-arthur-elgort-eric-von-stroh-wedding-southampton|title=Sophie Elgort and Eric Von Stroh's Wedding in Southampton|work=Vogue magazine|date=October 29, 2014|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref> was in the [[Norwegian resistance movement|Norwegian resistance]] during [[World War II]] and saved Norwegian Jewish children by moving them into neutral [[Sweden during World War II|Sweden]]; because of these activities, she was imprisoned in a [[Internment|concentration camp]].<ref name=nytob2/><ref name=divref2>{{cite web |date=February 24, 2014 |url=http://www.divergentlife.com/2014/02/new-ansel-elgort-live-stream-q-200k.html |title=Ansel Elgort's Live Stream |work=Divergent Society.net |quote=Quote stated at 16:40 in the interview. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227150346/http://divergentsociety.net/divergentmovie/ansel-elgorts-live-stream/ |archivedate=February 27, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Elgort is named after photographer [[Ansel Adams]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Millennial Man- Ansel Elgort |url=http://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/news/a2660/ansel-elgort/ |first=Carl |last=Swanson |date=January 6, 2015 |publisher=Town & Country}}</ref>\n\nThe third of three children, he has two older siblings: sister Sophie Elgort (born 1986), a fashion photographer,<ref name=vmagref1>{{cite magazine |last=Lamphier |first=Jason |title=Teenage Daydream |pages= |magazine=[[V (American magazine)|V]] |date=2013 |url=http://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/814/teenage-daydream |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825090245/http://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/814/teenage-daydream |archivedate=August 25, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ansel Elgort's Big Sis Is Launching a Lifestyle Website |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ansel-elgorts-sister-sophie-launching-798829 |first=Kathryn |last=Romeyn |date=May 29, 2015 |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> and brother Warren Elgort (born 1989), a cinematographer.<ref>{{cite web|first=Zachary|last=Weiss|url=http://observer.com/2016/07/21-young-new-york-socialites-you-should-know/|title=21 Young New York Socialites You Should Know|work=[[New York Observer]]|date=July 26, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref> At age nine, his mother took him to try out for [[School of American Ballet]].<ref name=vog1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/how-ansel-elgort-went-from-brother-to-lover-with-shailene-woodley-in-the-fault-in-our-stars-20140602-zrssf.html|title=How Ansel Elgort went from brother to lover with Shailene Woodley in The Fault in Our Stars|last=Cooney Carrillo|first=Jenny|date=May 30, 2014|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=|access-date=May 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/divergent-fault-stars-actor-ansel-687196|title=Next Big Thing: 'Divergent,' 'Fault in Our Stars' Actor Ansel Elgort (Video)|last=Ford|first=Rebecca|date=March 20, 2014|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=|access-date=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Elgort went on to study there for five years.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York city ballet gala|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/05/new-york-city-ballet-gala-ansel-elgort|date=May 4, 2018 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nElgort attended [[The Professional Performing Arts School]], [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School]] and [[Stagedoor Manor]] summer camp.<ref name=\"interviewmag1\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Ansel Elgort kicks acting career into high gear with 'Baby Driver' |url=http://torontosun.com/2017/06/23/ansel-elgort-kicks-acting-career-into-high-gear-with-baby-driver/wcm/01837a97-1cde-481f-9d23-7b3e7a10e00b |first=Liz |last=Braun |date=June 23, 2017 |work=[[Toronto Sun]]|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Audition Choice That Booked Ansel Elgort 'Baby Driver' |url=https://www.backstage.com/interview/audition-choice-booked-ansel-elgort-baby-driver/ |first=Benjamin|last=Lindsay|date=June 21, 2017|work=[[Backstage (magazine)|Backstage]]|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref> Elgort started taking acting classes at age 12 and at LaGuardia, where he performed in a rendition of ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' with schoolmate [[Kyle Jean-Baptiste]] and starred in the school's productions of ''[[Guys and Dolls]]''.<ref name=vog1 /><ref name=kylejeanbaptiste>{{cite magazine |title=Kyle Jean-Baptiste Dead: Les Miserables Broadway Actor Dies at 21 |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kyle-jean-baptiste-dead-les-miserables-broadway-actor-dies-at-21-2015298 |first=Stephanie |last=Webber |accessdate=August 29, 2015 |magazine=[[Us Weekly]] |date=August 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nElgort's first professional acting appearance was a few months before graduating high school, just days after his 18th birthday, when he premiered a lead role in an [[Off-Broadway]] production of ''Regrets'' in March 2012.<ref name=vog1 /> His film debut was in the 2013 remake of ''[[Carrie (2013 film)|Carrie]]'', in the key secondary role of the lead character's prom date. His first highly publicized role was in ''[[Divergent (film)|Divergent]]'' (2014) as Caleb Prior, the brother of the lead character.\n\nImmediately after the filming of ''Divergent'' was completed, it was announced that Elgort would play Augustus Waters in the film adaptation of [[John Green (author)|John Green's]] [[The Fault in Our Stars|novel]] ''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]'' opposite Woodley, who would play Hazel Grace Lancaster.<ref name=ew1>{{cite magazine |last=Vilkomerson |first=Sara |title=Ansel Elgort offered lead in 'The Fault in Our Stars' opposite Shailene Woodley |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |date=May 10, 2013 |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/05/10/ansel-elgort-gus-fault-in-our-stars |accessdate=May 10, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603122028/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/05/10/ansel-elgort-gus-fault-in-our-stars/ |archivedate=June 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The film followed the story of Hazel, a teenage cancer patient, who is forced by her parents to attend a support group, where she subsequently meets and falls in love with Waters, an ex-basketball player. The film, directed by [[Josh Boone (director)|Josh Boone]], was released on June 6, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last=Goldberg |first=Matt |title=First Clip from \"The Fault In Our Stars\" starring Shailene Woodley and Ansel Elgort |url=https://collider.com/the-fault-in-our-stars-clip/ |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=April 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418233858/http://collider.com/the-fault-in-our-stars-clip/ |archivedate=April 18, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Elgort next co-starred in the dramatic film ''[[Men, Women & Children (film)|Men, Women & Children]]'', directed by [[Jason Reitman]] and released in October 2014.<ref name=HR1>{{cite news |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |title=Jason Reitman's 'Men, Women & Children' Adds Emma Thompson, Judy Greer, Dean Norris |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jason-reitmans-men-women-children-665958 |accessdate=December 18, 2013 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |date=December 16, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218021436/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jason-reitmans-men-women-children-665958 |archivedate=December 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n[[File:Ansel Elgort 2014 Divergent Premiere (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Elgort at the premiere of ''Divergent'', 2014]]\nIn 2014, Elgort was named one of the best actors under 20 years of age.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |first1=The Playlist |title=On The Rise: 20 Actors To Watch That Are Under 20 |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/09/on-the-rise-20-actors-to-watch-that-are-under-20-272876/ |website=Indiewire |accessdate=February 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217143828/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/09/on-the-rise-20-actors-to-watch-that-are-under-20-272876/ |archivedate=February 17, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Elgort reunited with [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] to present the award for Best Visual Effects at the 2015 [[Oscars]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giardina |first=Carolyn |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-2015-best-visual-effects-773989 |title=Oscars 2015: Best Visual Effects: Interstellar Wins Award |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |date=February 22, 2015 |accessdate=October 12, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009145043/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-2015-best-visual-effects-773989 |archivedate=October 9, 2015 |df= }}</ref> He also reprised his role, Caleb Prior, in ''[[The Divergent Series: Insurgent]]'', the second film of the book series ''Divergent'', which was released March 20, 2015, and in the third film, ''[[The Divergent Series: Allegiant]]'', which was released on March 18, 2016.\n\nIn 2016, Elgort was on a shortlist of actors for the role of [[Han Solo]] in ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''. After [[Alden Ehrenreich]] was cast in May 2016, Elgort expressed some relief, saying that if he had been cast, he would have had to change his DJ name, Ans\u00f8lo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's The One Upside To Not Getting The New Han Solo Role |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/ansel-elgort-han-solo_us_57960a8ee4b02d5d5ed219cf |first=Todd |last=Van Luling |date=July 25, 2016 |work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Elgort played the title role in the action film ''[[Baby Driver]]'', directed by [[Edgar Wright]], and also starring [[Lily James]] and [[Kevin Spacey]]. Elgort's audition in 2014 required him to [[lip sync]] and dance to the song of his choosing.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Milzoff|first1=Rebecca|title=Ansel Elgort Breaks Out With 'Baby Driver' and a Frank Ocean-Approved Singing Career: 'I'm Hopefully Going to Pull It All Off'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7832934/ansel-elgort-baby-driver-2017-cover-story|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 18, 2017|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> The film received positive reviews and performed well at the box office. He received a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] nomination for it.<ref name=\"gg17\">{{cite news|author1=Merry, Stephanie|first=Yahr, Emily|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/12/11/golden-globes-nominations-2018-complete-coverage/ |title=Golden Globes nominations 2018: Complete list of nominations |date=December 11, 2017 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 11, 2017 }}</ref> Also that year, Elgort played Addison Schacht in the drama thriller film ''[[November Criminals (film)|November Criminals]]'', an adaptation of the novel of [[The November Criminals|the same name]], starring again with Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2015/ansel-elgort-to-join-november-criminals-with-chloe-grace-moretz/ |title=Ansel Elgort to Join 'November Criminals' with Chloe Grace Moretz |website=FirstShowing.net |date=August 1, 2015 |accessdate=October 12, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924050902/http://www.firstshowing.net/2015/ansel-elgort-to-join-november-criminals-with-chloe-grace-moretz/ |archivedate=September 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nElgort stars in the film ''[[Billionaire Boys Club (2018 film)|Billionaire Boys Club]]'', opposite [[Kevin Spacey]], [[Cary Elwes]], [[Emma Roberts]] and [[Taron Egerton]] and directed by [[James Cox (director)|James Cox]]. Due to claims of sexual harassment against Spacey, the future of the film was uncertain and no release date was set.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/these-upcoming-kevin-spacey-movies-shows-may-be-in-trouble-now.html/?a=viewall|title=These Upcoming Kevin Spacey Projects May Be in Trouble Now|date=2017-12-01|work=The Cheat Sheet|access-date=2018-03-10|language=en-US}}</ref> The film was initially released through [[video on demand]] on July 17, 2018, prior to a [[limited release]] in theaters on August 17, 2018, by [[Vertical Entertainment]].<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kevin-spacey-movie-billionaire-boys-club-hit-theaters-1121334 Kevin Spacey Film 'Billionaire Boys Club' to Hit Select Theaters in August]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/kevin-spaceys-billionaire-boys-club-to-hit-theaters-in-august/|title=Return From Exile: Kevin Spacey's 'Billionaire Boys Club' to Hit Theaters in August (Exclusive)|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Matt|last=Donelly|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> Elgort played the lead role in the 2019 release ''[[The Goldfinch (film)|The Goldfinch]]'', an adaptation of [[Donna Tartt]]'s novel.\n\n====Upcoming films====\nOn June 27, 2017, it was announced that Elgort would portray future [[President of the United States|President]] [[John F. Kennedy]] during his time in the [[United States Navy]] in the film ''Mayday 109''.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/06/27/ansel-elgort-young-jfk-mayday-109/ |title=Ansel Elgort cast as young JFK in Mayday 109 |last=Gettell |first=Oliver |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |location=United States |date=June 27, 2017 |accessdate=June 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628013442/http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/27/ansel-elgort-young-jfk-mayday-109/ |archivedate=June 28, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2018, it was reported that Elgort would costar alongside [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] and [[Zendaya]] in [[crime thriller]] ''Finest Kind'', in which two brothers, portrayed by Elgort and Gyllenhaal, \"strike a dangerous deal with a crime syndicate that draws them into the Boston underworld\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/jake-gyllenhaal-ansel-elgort-zendaya-finest-kind-movie-1202283940/|title=Jake Gyllenhaal, Ansel Elgort & Zendaya To Topline  Crime Thriller 'Finest Kind'|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=February 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2018, it was revealed that Elgort would star as [[Hans Christian Andersen]] in an untitled original [[musical film]] with music composed by [[Stephen Schwartz (composer)|Stephen Schwartz]] and script provided by [[David Magee]]. The film would find Elgort as Hans, \"a young man who trapped in a world of his own imagination. And as Hans searches for a way back to reality, he comes face-to-face with characters from his own fairy tales, nearly all of whom try to trap him in their world forever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/ansel-elgort-hans-christian-andersen-musical-wicked-stephen-schwartz-craig-zadan-neil-meron-fox-2000-david-magee-1202305862/|title=Fox 2000 Wins Hans Christian Andersen Musical By 'Wicked's Stephen Schwartz, David Magee, Zadan & Meron; 'Baby Driver' Ansel Elgort Circling|first=Mike Fleming|last=Jr|date=February 28, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2018, it was reported that Elgort had been cast in the lead role of Tony in director [[Steven Spielberg]]'s adaptation of ''[[West Side Story]]''. Filming commenced at the end of September 2019.<ref>[https://variety.com/2018/film/news/ansel-elgort-west-side-story-steven-spielberg-1202964116/#article-comments Ansel Elgort to Star in Steven Spielberg's 'West Side Story']</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, it was announced that Elgort would be starring as the title character in a film adaptation of \"The Great High School Impostor\". The film is based on the true story of Artur Samarin, a Ukrainian man who in 2012 overstayed his visa and then posed as an American high school student from the ages of 19\u201323 years old. The film will be made by Participant Media and scripted by Mike Makowsky.<ref>Gary, Collinson (December 21, 2018). [https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2018/12/ansel-elgort-is-the-great-high-school-imposter/ \"Ansel Elgort is the Great High School Impostor.\"] Retrieved April 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, it was announced that Elgort would play the role of American journalist [[Jake Adelstein]] in a television adaptation of Adelstein's non-fiction memoir ''[[Tokyo Vice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joe Otterson |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/ansel-elgort-tokyo-vice-warnermedia-streaming-service-1203235293 |title=Ansel Elgort to Star in Drama Series \u2018Tokyo Vice\u2019 for WarnerMedia \u2013 Variety |website=Variety.com |date=2019-06-06 |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Nellie Andreeva |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/warnermedia-streamer-orders-tokyo-vice-drama-series-ansel-elgort-endeavor-content-1202628306 |title=WarnerMedia Streamer Orders \u2018Tokyo Vice\u2019 Series Starring Ansel Elgort \u2013 Deadline |website=Deadline.com |date=2019-06-06 |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> The ten-part television series tells the story of an American journalist who embeds himself into the Tokyo Vice police squad to reveal corruption. The series will be written and executive produced by Tony Award-winning playwright [[J. T. Rogers]], with the pilot episode directed by [[Michael Mann]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Fleming Jr |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/michael-mann-direct-pilot-tokyo-vice-ansel-elgort-ken-watanabe-hbo-max-1202766347/ |title=Michael Mann Direct Ansel Elgort Ken Watanabe HBO Max Pilot Tokyo Vice \u2013 Deadline |website=Deadline.com |date=2019-10-22 |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> and subsequent episodes directed by [[Destin Daniel Cretton]] (''Short Term 12'').  Endeavor Content will serve as the studio and [[John Lesher (producer)|John Lesher]] and [[Emily Gerson Saines]] will serve as executive producers, alongside Elgort, Rogers, and Mann. Tokyo Vice will debut on [[WarnerMedia]]'s upcoming streaming platform [[HBO Max]].\n\nElgort is represented by [[Creative Artists Agency|CAA]] and Brookside Artist Management's Emily Gerson Saines.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=https://deadline.com/2014/06/ansel-elgort-fault-in-our-stars-van-cliburn-movie-794404/ |title='Fault In Our Stars' Ansel Elgort To Play Van Cliburn In Biopic |website=Deadline |date=June 23, 2014 |accessdate=October 12, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019070354/http://deadline.com/2014/06/ansel-elgort-fault-in-our-stars-van-cliburn-movie-794404/ |archivedate=October 19, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[File:Ansel Elgort at an Apple Store in 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Elgort in 2014]]\nUnder the name Ansolo, Elgort created a [[SoundCloud]] account to publish electronic dance music, and he has remixed songs such as \"[[Born to Die (song)|Born to Die]]\" by [[Lana del Rey]]. In a livestream in February 2014, he said he had signed a record deal with Tom Staar's new label, Staar Traxx, and [[Steve Angello]]'s label, Size Records.{{citation needed |date=August 2014}}\n\nHis first record, ''Unite'', was released on April 21, 2014, on [[Beatport]], and May 5, 2014, on [[iTunes]].<ref name=THR>{{cite magazine |author1=Ashley Lee |title=Ansel Elgort to Release Electronic Dance Music Record 'Unite' in April (Audio) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/audio-ansel-elgort-electronic-dance-music-unite-690256 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |date=March 21, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720043821/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/audio-ansel-elgort-electronic-dance-music-unite-690256 |archivedate=July 20, 2014 |df= }}</ref> His second record, ''Totem'', was released July 21, 2014, on Beatport and iTunes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crossmap.com/news/ansel-elgort-aka-ansolos-totem-enters-top-music-charts-video-talks-musical-career-in-intimate-interview-11434 |title=Ansel Elgort AKA Ansolo's 'Totem' Enters Top Music Charts [VIDEO] Talks Musical Career in Intimate Interview |first=Alma L. |last=Cruz |website=Crossmap |date=July 22, 2014 |accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref> His single \"To Life\", a [[Bar and Bat Mitzvah|Bar Mitzvah]]-themed song inflected with [[klezmer]] music, was released in September 2015.<ref name=bb/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2275615/ansel-elgort-ansolo-to-life/ |title=Here's 'To Life,' A Brand-Spanking-New Song From Ansolo (AKA Ansel Elgort) |work=MTV News |first=Patrick |last=Hosken |date=September 18, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409142031/http://www.mtv.com/news/2275615/ansel-elgort-ansolo-to-life/ |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nElgort played at the [[Electric Zoo Festival]] main stage in 2014, the [[Ultra Music Festival]] main stage in March 2015, played in a red-light dance music event in [[Amsterdam]] in 2014, opened some [[The Chainsmokers]] shows, a [[Nervo (duo)|Nervo]] show and some others shows with his friends [[Nicky Romero]] and [[Martin Garrix]]. He played his first headline show on his 21st birthday on [[Pacha Group|Pacha NYC]].\n\nIn 2015, he signed a record deal with Island/Universal Records, releasing his first single on the label, \"Home Alone\", in July 8, 2016.\n \nOn February 3, 2017, he released a single called \"Thief\" under the name Ansel Elgort. The music video featured his girlfriend Violetta Komyshan, a [[ballet dancer]].\n\nHe was featured on rapper [[Logic (musician)|Logic]]'s third studio album, ''[[Everybody (Logic album)|Everybody]]'', released on May 5, 2017, on a song titled \"Killing Spree\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/05/stream-new-logic-album-everybody/ |title=Stream Logic's New Album 'Everybody' |magazine=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]] |accessdate=May 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505095636/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/05/stream-new-logic-album-everybody/ |archivedate=May 5, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2018, he released a single called \"Supernova\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q-oM2BQ8Jow|title=Ansel Elgort - Supernova|first=|last=AnselElgortVEVO|date=January 11, 2018|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2012, Elgort began dating his high school sweetheart, Violetta Komyshan, a ballet dancer. The couple broke up in August 2014 primarily due to the actor's burgeoning career and hectic schedule<ref>{{cite web |title=Ansel Elgort and High School Sweetheart Violetta Komyshan Break Up |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/573818/ansel-elgort-and-high-school-sweetheart-violetta-komyshan-break-up |work=eonline.com |first=Lily |last=Harrison |date=August 27, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217192735/http://www.eonline.com/news/573818/ansel-elgort-and-high-school-sweetheart-violetta-komyshan-break-up |archivedate=February 17, 2015 |df= }}</ref> but reconciled in 2015.\n\nHe is a [[skateboarding|skateboarder]] and an avid sportsman, often seen playing pickup basketball. As a hobby, he also took to [[Figure painting (hobby)|miniature painting]], displaying some of his work.<ref name=bb/> He is an avid fan of the [[New York Mets]], [[New York Jets]], [[New York Knicks]] and [[New York Rangers]].\n\nHe currently resides in the Bedford Stuyvesant neighborhood in Brooklyn, NY.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | 