t'''}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Killing Spree\" <br><small>([[Logic (musician)|Logic]] feat. Ansel Elgort)</small>\n| 2017\n| ''[[Everybody (Logic album)|Everybody]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Believe\" <br><small>([[Don Diablo]] feat. Ansel Elgort)</small>\n| 2018\n| ''[[Future (Don Diablo album)|Future]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/future-deluxe-edition/1360383527|title=FUTURE (Deluxe Edition) by Don Diablo on Apple Music (CA)|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Artist\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Notes\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Dua Lipa]]\n|\"[[Be the One (Dua Lipa song)|Be the One]]\"\n|2016\n|Daniel Kaufman\n| Guest appearance\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mgI_pH8TOVY |title=Dua Lipa - Be The One (Official Video) |author=Vevo |date=December 5, 2016 |website=YouTube |accessdate=July 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617124135/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mgI_pH8TOVY |archivedate=June 17, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ansel Elgort\n|\"Thief\"\n| 2017\n| Warren Elgort\n| \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vevo.com/watch/ansel-elgort/Thief/USUV71700085 |title=\"Thief\" by Ansel Elgort |website=[[Vevo]] |accessdate=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ansel Elgort\n|\"Supernova\"\n| 2018\n| Colin Tilley\n| \n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vevo.com/watch/ansel-elgort/supernova/USUV71704945 |title=\"Supernova\" by Ansel Elgort |website=[[Vevo]]}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[J.I.D]]\n|\"Off da Zoinkys\"\n| 2019\n| Scott Lazer\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| style=\"width:75%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10px;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Award\n! style=\"width:220px;\"| Nominated work\n! style=\"width:30px;\"| Result\n! style=\"width:10px;\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=6|2014\n|[[2014 Teen Choice Awards|Choice Movie: Liplock]] {{small|(shared with [[Shailene Woodley]])}}\n|rowspan=2|''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]''\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|[[2014 Teen Choice Awards|Choice Movie: Chemistry]] {{small|(shared with [[Shailene Woodley]] and [[Nat Wolff]])}}\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|[[2014 Young Hollywood Awards|Fan Favorite Actor \u2013 Male]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]'' / ''[[Divergent (film)|Divergent]]''\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|[[2014 Young Hollywood Awards|Breakthrough Actor]]\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[2014 Young Hollywood Awards|Best On-Screen Couple]] {{small|(shared with [[Shailene Woodley]])}}\n|rowspan=\"9\" | ''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]''\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n| Best New Film Actor\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\" | 2015\n| Favorite Movie Duo {{small|(shared with [[Shailene Woodley]])}}\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Young Performer|Best Young Actor/Actress]]\n| {{nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|Best Male Performance\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|Breakthrough Performance\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|Best Shirtless Performance\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|Best Kiss {{small|(shared with [[Shailene Woodley]])}}\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|Best Duo {{small|(shared with [[Shailene Woodley]])}}\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Teen Choice Awards|Choice Movie Actor: Action]]\n|''[[The Divergent Series: Insurgent]]''\n|{{nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n|rowspan=3|''[[Baby Driver]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"gg17\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|[[Empire Award for Best Male Newcomer]]\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[MTV Movie Award for Best Actor in a Movie|MTV Movie Award for Best Performance in a Movie]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/mtv-movie-tv-awards-2018-nominations-complete-list-1108100 |title=MTV Movie & TV Awards: 'Black Panther,' 'Stranger Things' Top Nominations |last=Nordyke |first=Kimberly |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 3, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503235147/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/mtv-movie-tv-awards-2018-nominations-complete-list-1108100 |archivedate=May 3, 2018 |df=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ansel Elgort}}\n* {{SoundCloud}}\n* {{IMDb name|5052065|Ansel Elgort}}\n\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elgort, Ansel}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Russian descent]]\n", "name_user": "156.204.252.5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansel_Elgort"}
{"title_page": "Dihya", "text_new": "{{short description|Berber warrior queen who resisted the Umayyad conquest of the Maghreb}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n| name = Dihya\n| title =\n| image= Statue of Dyhia in Khenchela (Algeria).jpg\n| caption = Dihya memorial in [[Khenchela]], [[Algeria]]\n| reign = Early seventh century\n| coronation =\n| full name =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = 703 CE\n| death_place = [[Biskra]]\n| burial_date =\n| burial_place = [[Khenchela]]\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| spouse =\n| issue =\n| royal house =\n| dynasty =\n| father =\n| mother =\n| religion =\n}}\n'Damia Mfak ''Dihya''' or '''Kahina''' was a [[Berbers|Berber]] warrior queen and a religious and military leader who led indigenous resistance to the [[Muslim conquest of the Maghreb]], the region then known as [[Numidia]]. She was born in the early 7th century and died around the end of the 7th century in modern-day [[Algeria]].\n\n==Origins and religion==\n{{refimprove|section|date=February 2017}}\nHer personal name is one of these variations: Daya, Dehiya, Dihya, Dahya or Damya.<ref>See discussion of these supposed names by Talbi (1971).</ref> Her title was cited by Arabic-language sources as ''al-K\u0101hina'' (the [[priest]]ess [[divination|soothsayer]]). This was the nickname given to by her [[Muslim]] opponents because of her alleged ability to foresee the future.\n\nShe was born into the [[Jarawa (Berber)|Jr\u0101wa]] [[Zenata]] tribe in the early 7th century.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1jfzkJTAZgC|title=North Africa: A History from Antiquity to the Present|last=Naylor|first=Phillip C.|year=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=|page=65|language=en|isbn=978-0292778788}}</ref>\n\nFor five years she ruled a free Berber state from the [[Aur\u00e8s Mountains]] to the oasis of [[Gadames]] (695\u2013700 CE).\n\nBut the Arabs, commanded by [[Musa bin Nusayr]], returned with a strong army and defeated her. She fought at the [[El Djem]] Roman amphitheater but finally was killed in combat near a well that still bears her name, ''Bir al Kahina'' in [[Aures, Algeria|Aures]].<ref name=\"JulienTourneau1970\">{{cite book|author1=Charles Andr\u00e9 Julien|author2=Roger Le Tourneau|title=Histoire de L'Afrique du Nord|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tYZyAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Praeger|page=13}}</ref>\n\nAccounts from the 19th century on claim she was of [[Berber Jews|Jewish]] religion or that her [[tribe]] were [[Berber Jews|Judaized]] [[Berbers]].<ref>See Hirschberg (1963) and Talbi (1971).</ref> According to [[Abu Bakr ibn al-Arabi|al-M\u0101lik\u012b]], she was accompanied in her travels by an \"idol\". Both [[Mohamed Talbi]] and [[Gabriel Camps]] interpreted this idol as a Christian icon, either of Christ, the Virgin, or a saint protecting the queen. [[M'hamed Hassine Fantar]] held that this icon represented a separate Berber deity, and thus made Dihya a pagan. However, Dihya being a Christian remains the most likely hypothesis.<ref name=\"EB1306\">{{Cite encyclopedia|year=2005|title=Kahena|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e9die berb\u00e8re]]|publisher=Edisud|chapter-url=https://journals.openedition.org/encyclopedieberbere/1306|last=Mod\u00e9ran|first=Yves|authorlink=Yves Mod\u00e9ran|location=Aix-en-Provence|volume=27 {{!}} Kairouan \u2013 Kifan Bel-Ghomari|pages=4102\u20134111|isbn=978-2744905384|chapter=Kahena. (Al-K\u00e2hina)}}</ref>\n\nThe idea that the Jarawa were [[Judaized]] comes from the medieval historian [[Ibn Khaldun]], who named them among seven Berber tribes. Hirschberg and Talbi note that Ibn Khaldun seems to have been referring to a time before the advent of the late [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and [[Byzantine]] empires, and a little later in the same paragraph seems to say that by [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] times \"the tribes\" had become [[Christianized]]. As early as 1963, the Israeli historian H.Z. Hirschberg, in retranslating the text of Ibn Khaldun and rigorously repeating the whole document, questioned this interpretation, and in general the existence of large Jewish Berber tribes in the end of Antiquity.<ref name=\"EB1306\" /> In the words of H.Z. Hirschberg, \"of all the known movements of conversion to [[Judaism]] and incidents of [[Judaizing]], those connected with the [[Berbers]] and [[Sudan]]ese in [[Africa]] are the least authenticated. Whatever has been written on them is extremely questionable.\"<ref>Hirschberg (1963) p. 339.</ref>\n\nOver four centuries after her death, Tunisian [[hagiographer]] al-M\u0101lik\u012b seems to have been among the first to state she resided in the [[Aur\u00e8s Mountains]]. Just seven centuries after her death, the pilgrim at-Tijani was told she belonged to the [[Luwata|L\u016bw\u0101ta]] tribe.<ref>at-Tijani, Arabic text p. 57: ''al-k\u0101hinat al-ma'ar\u016bfat bi-k\u0101hinat l\u016bw\u0101tat'', p. 118 of the translation</ref> When the later historian Ibn Khaldun came to write his account, he placed her with the Jarawa tribe.\n\nAccording to various Muslim sources, al-K\u0101hinat was the daughter of [[Tabat]], or some say M\u0101tiya.<ref>According to some, this name is an Arabicized form of the Christian name Matthias or Matthew. See Talbi (1971) for more discussion.</ref> These sources depend on [[tribal]] [[genealogies]], which were generally concocted for political reasons during the 9th century.<ref>Talbi (1971) and Mod\u00e9ran (2005) discuss the various sources.</ref>\n\nIbn Khaldun records many legends about Dihy\u0101. A number of them refer to her long [[hair]] or great size, both legendary characteristics of [[Magician (paranormal)|sorcerers]]. She is also supposed to have had the gift of [[prophecy]] and she had three sons, which is characteristic of witches in legends. Even the fact that two were her own and one was adopted (an [[Arab]] officer she had captured) was an alleged trait of sorcerers in tales. Another [[legend]] claims that in her youth, she had supposedly freed her people from a [[tyrant]] by agreeing to marry him and then murdering him on their [[wedding]] night. Virtually nothing else of her personal life is known.{{According to whom|date=May 2016}}\n\n== Conflicts and legends ==\n\nDihya succeeded [[Kusaila]] as the war leader of the [[Berber people|Berber]] tribes in the 680s and opposed the encroaching Arab Islamic armies of the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad Dynasty]]. [[Hasan ibn al-Nu'man]] marched from [[Egypt]] and captured the major [[Byzantine]] city of [[Carthage]] and other cities (see [[Muslim conquest of the Maghreb|Muslim conquest of North Africa]]). Searching for another enemy to defeat, he was told that the most powerful monarch in North Africa was \"the Queen of the Berbers\" (Arabic: ''malikat al-barbar'') Dihy\u0101, and accordingly marched into [[Numidia]]. In 698, the armies met near [[Meskiana]]<ref>Talbi (1971) suggests that based on the topography reported by al-M\u0101lik\u012b, the actual battlefield was the Wadi N\u012bn\u012b.</ref> in the present-day province of [[Oum el-Bouaghi Province|Oum el-Bouaghi]] at the {{ill|Battle of Meskiana|fr|Bataille de l'oued Nini}} (or \"battle of camels\") in [[Algeria]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Philippe S\u00e9nac|author2=Patrice Cressier|title=Histoire du Maghreb m\u00e9di\u00e9val: VIIe-XIe si\u00e8cle|editor=Armand Colin|year=2012|page=111|language=French|isbn=}}</ref> She defeated Hasan so soundly that he fled [[Ifriqiya]] and holed up in [[Cyrenaica]] (Libya) for four or five years. Realizing that the enemy was too powerful and bound to return, she was said to have embarked on a [[scorched earth]] campaign, which had little impact on the mountain and desert tribes, but lost her the crucial support of the sedentary oasis-dwellers. Instead of discouraging the Arab armies, her desperate decision hastened defeat.<ref>However, even if true, the Arab accounts are considered to be greatly exaggerated. See Talbi (1971) and Mod\u00e9ran (2005). One thing that is certain is that Dihy\u0101 loved ornithology.</ref>\n\nThe story of the Kahina is told by a variety of cultures, and each story often offers a different, or even contradictory, perspective. For example, the story is used to promote feminist beliefs. Additionally, it is even told by Arabs to promote their own nationalism. For the Arabs, they told the story in a perspective that made the Kahina seem like a sorcerer, all in an attempt to discredit her. Some Arab historians took it even farther by saying that the Kahina eventually tried to have her sons adopt Islam as their religion. Another group that told the story of the Kahina was the French. The story of the Kahina was told to paint colonialism in a positive light. The story was told with a message saying that it represented the freeing of Berbers from the Arabs.<ref name=Becker>Becker, Cynthia, [http://www.mizanproject.org/the-kahina-the-female-face-of-berber-history/#_ftn2 \"The Kahina: The Female Face of Berber History\"]. Mizan Project. October 26, 2015. Accessed April 15, 2018.</ref>\n\nAnother, lesser known account of Dihy\u0101 claimed that she had an interest in early studies of desert birds. While this view may or may not be plausible, some evidence has been recovered at the site of her death place, modern-day Algeria. Several fragments of early parchment with a painting of a bird on them were found, although there's no way to conclude the fragments were hers. However, it is possible that she began her interest while in Libya, as the painting was of a Libyan bird species.{{According to whom|date=May 2016}}\n\n== Defeat and death ==\n\n[[Hasan ibn al-Nu'man|Hasan]] eventually returned and, aided by communications with the captured officer \"Khalid bin Yazid al-Qaysi\" adopted by Dihya, defeated her at [[Tabarka]] (a locality in present-day [[Tunisia]] near the [[Algeria]]n borders)<ref name=\"EB1306\" /> about which there is some uncertainty.<ref>Talbi (1971) suggests it was between Setif and Tobna but this is not certain.</ref> According to some accounts, Dihya died fighting the invaders, sword in hand, a warrior's death. Other accounts say she committed suicide by swallowing poison rather than be taken by the enemy. This final act occurred in the 690s or 700s, with 703 CE given as the most likely year.<ref name=\"EB1306\" /> In that year, she was, according to [[Ibn Khaldun]], 127 years old. This is evidently yet another of the many myths which surround her.\n\nAccording to many historians,{{Who|date=June 2018}}{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} her sons Bagay and Khanchla converted, and led the Berber army to [[Iberia]]. However, the historian [[Ali ibn al-Athir|Ibn al-Ath\u012br]] says they died with their mother.\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{refimprove|section|date=January 2017}}\n\nIn later centuries, Dihy\u0101's legend was used to bolster the claims of Berbers in [[al-Andalus]] against Arab claims of ethnic supremacy\u2014in the early modern age, she was used by French colonials, Berber nationalists, North African Jews, North African feminists, and Maghrebi nationalists alike for their own didactic purposes.\n\nIn the present day, the image of the Kahina is constantly used by Berber activists to showcase how they, as a people, are strong and will not be conquered or diminished by other communities. Her face is often seen in graffiti and sculptures around Algeria to showcase their support for the progressive ideals she represents. While her true appearance is still unknown, artists have depicted her with certain aspects that reinforce the progressive movement she is known to represent. However, not all governments accept the ideals behind the Kahina. One statue of the Kahina in Bagha\u00ef was condemned by the government due to blasphemy. The president said that the Kahina represented the resistance of Islam, and thus, should be condemned.<ref name=Becker />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|History|Feminism}}\n* [[Umayyad conquest of North Africa]]\n* [[Kusaila]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Ibn Khaldun]], ''Kit\u0101b al-Ibar''. Usually cited as: ''Histoire des Berb\u00e8res et des dynasties musulmanes de l'Afrique septentrionale'', a French trans. by William McGuckin de Slane, Paul Geuthner, Paris, 1978. This 19th-century translation should now be regarded as obsolete. There is a more accurate modern French translation by Abdesselam Cheddadi, ''Peuples et Nations du Monde: extraits des Ibar'', Sindbad, Paris, 1986 & 1995. Hirschberg (1963) gives an English translation of the section where [[Ibn Khaldun]] discusses the supposed Judaized Jar\u0101wa.\n* Hannoum, Abdelmajid. (2001). ''Post-Colonial Memories: The Legend of the Dihy\u0101, a North African Heroine'' (''Studies in [[African literature|African Literature]]''). {{ISBN|0-325-00253-3}}. This is a study of the legend of the Dihy\u0101 in the 19th century and later. The first chapter is a detailed critique of how the legend of the Dihy\u0101 emerged after several transformations from the 9th century to the 14th.\n* {{Cite journal|last=Hirschberg|first=H.Z.|date=November 1963|title=The Problem of the Judaized Berbers|journal=The Journal of African History|language=en|volume=4|issue=3|pages=313\u2013339|doi=10.1017/S0021853700004278|issn=1469-5138}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LcxtAAAAMAAJ|title=A History of the Jews in North Africa|last=Hirschberg|first=H.Z.|publisher=Brill|year=1974|isbn=978-9004038202|edition=2nd ed., Eng. trans.|volume=Volume 1 From Antiquity to the Sixteenth Century|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n* al-M\u0101lik\u012b, ''Riy\u0101d an-Nuf\u016bs''. Partial French trans. (including the story of the Dihy\u0101) by H.R. Idris, 'Le r\u00e9cit d'al-M\u0101lik\u012b sur la Conqu\u00eate de l'Ifr\u012bqiya', ''Revue des Etudes Islamiques'' 37 (1969) 117\u2013149. The accuracy of this translation has been criticised by Talbi (1971) and others.\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|year=2005|title=Kahena|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e9die berb\u00e8re]]|publisher=Edisud|chapter-url=https://journals.openedition.org/encyclopedieberbere/1306|last=Mod\u00e9ran|first=Yves|authorlink=Yves Mod\u00e9ran|location=Aix-en-Provence|volume=27 {{!}} Kairouan \u2013 Kifan Bel-Ghomari|pages=4102\u20134111|isbn=978-2744905384|chapter=Kahena. (Al-K\u00e2hina)}} The most recent critical study of the historical sources.\n* Talbi, Mohammed. (1971). ''Un nouveau fragment de l'histoire de l'Occident musulman (62\u2013196/682\u2013812) : l'\u00e9pop\u00e9e d'al Kahina.'' (''Cahiers de Tunisie'' vol. 19 pp.&nbsp;19\u201352). An important historiographical study.\n* at-Tij\u0101n\u012b, ''Rihlat''. Arabic text ed. by H.H. Abdulwahhab, Johann Wolfgang Goethe University, Frankfurt, 1994. French trans. by A. Rousseau in ''Journal Asiatique'', section containing the story of the Dihy\u0101 is in n.s. 4, vol. 20 (1852) 57\u2013208.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:7th-century births]]\n[[Category:703 deaths]]\n[[Category:African women in war]]\n[[Category:7th-century Berber people]]\n[[Category:Women rulers in Africa]]\n[[Category:Medieval Algeria]]\n[[Category:Muslim conquest of the Maghreb]]\n[[Category:Women in medieval warfare]]\n[[Category:Zenata]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Place of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Place of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Berber Christians]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Algeria]]\n[[Category:7th-century monarchs in Africa]]\n[[Category:7th-century women]]\n[[Category:Queens regnant]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Berber warrior queen who resisted the Umayyad conquest of the Maghreb}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n| name = Dihya\n| title =\n| image= Statue of Dyhia in Khenchela (Algeria).jpg\n| caption = Dihya memorial in [[Khenchela]], [[Algeria]]\n| reign = Early seventh century\n| coronation =\n| full name =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = 703 CE\n| death_place = [[Biskra]]\n| burial_date =\n| burial_place = [[Khenchela]]\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| spouse =\n| issue =\n| royal house =\n| dynasty =\n| father =\n| mother =\n| religion =\n}}\n'''Dihya''' or '''Kahina''' was a [[Berbers|Berber]] warrior queen and a religious and military leader who led indigenous resistance to the [[Muslim conquest of the Maghreb]], the region then known as [[Numidia]]. She was born in the early 7th century and died around the end of the 7th century in modern-day [[Algeria]].\n\n==Origins and religion==\n{{refimprove|section|date=February 2017}}\nHer personal name is one of these variations: Daya, Dehiya, Dihya, Dahya or Damya.<ref>See discussion of these supposed names by Talbi (1971).</ref> Her title was cited by Arabic-language sources as ''al-K\u0101hina'' (the [[priest]]ess [[divination|soothsayer]]). This was the nickname given to by her [[Muslim]] opponents because of her alleged ability to foresee the future.\n\nShe was born into the [[Jarawa (Berber)|Jr\u0101wa]] [[Zenata]] tribe in the early 7th century.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1jfzkJTAZgC|title=North Africa: A History from Antiquity to the Present|last=Naylor|first=Phillip C.|year=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=|page=65|language=en|isbn=978-0292778788}}</ref>\n\nFor five years she ruled a free Berber state from the [[Aur\u00e8s Mountains]] to the oasis of [[Gadames]] (695\u2013700 CE).\n\nBut the Arabs, commanded by [[Musa bin Nusayr]], returned with a strong army and defeated her. She fought at the [[El Djem]] Roman amphitheater but finally was killed in combat near a well that still bears her name, ''Bir al Kahina'' in [[Aures, Algeria|Aures]].<ref name=\"JulienTourneau1970\">{{cite book|author1=Charles Andr\u00e9 Julien|author2=Roger Le Tourneau|title=Histoire de L'Afrique du Nord|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tYZyAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Praeger|page=13}}</ref>\n\nAccounts from the 19th century on claim she was of [[Berber Jews|Jewish]] religion or that her [[tribe]] were [[Berber Jews|Judaized]] [[Berbers]].<ref>See Hirschberg (1963) and Talbi (1971).</ref> According to [[Abu Bakr ibn al-Arabi|al-M\u0101lik\u012b]], she was accompanied in her travels by an \"idol\". Both [[Mohamed Talbi]] and [[Gabriel Camps]] interpreted this idol as a Christian icon, either of Christ, the Virgin, or a saint protecting the queen. [[M'hamed Hassine Fantar]] held that this icon represented a separate Berber deity, and thus made Dihya a pagan. However, Dihya being a Christian remains the most likely hypothesis.<ref name=\"EB1306\">{{Cite encyclopedia|year=2005|title=Kahena|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e9die berb\u00e8re]]|publisher=Edisud|chapter-url=https://journals.openedition.org/encyclopedieberbere/1306|last=Mod\u00e9ran|first=Yves|authorlink=Yves Mod\u00e9ran|location=Aix-en-Provence|volume=27 {{!}} Kairouan \u2013 Kifan Bel-Ghomari|pages=4102\u20134111|isbn=978-2744905384|chapter=Kahena. (Al-K\u00e2hina)}}</ref>\n\nThe idea that the Jarawa were [[Judaized]] comes from the medieval historian [[Ibn Khaldun]], who named them among seven Berber tribes. Hirschberg and Talbi note that Ibn Khaldun seems to have been referring to a time before the advent of the late [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and [[Byzantine]] empires, and a little later in the same paragraph seems to say that by [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] times \"the tribes\" had become [[Christianized]]. As early as 1963, the Israeli historian H.Z. Hirschberg, in retranslating the text of Ibn Khaldun and rigorously repeating the whole document, questioned this interpretation, and in general the existence of large Jewish Berber tribes in the end of Antiquity.<ref name=\"EB1306\" /> In the words of H.Z. Hirschberg, \"of all the known movements of conversion to [[Judaism]] and incidents of [[Judaizing]], those connected with the [[Berbers]] and [[Sudan]]ese in [[Africa]] are the least authenticated. Whatever has been written on them is extremely questionable.\"<ref>Hirschberg (1963) p. 339.</ref>\n\nOver four centuries after her death, Tunisian [[hagiographer]] al-M\u0101lik\u012b seems to have been among the first to state she resided in the [[Aur\u00e8s Mountains]]. Just seven centuries after her death, the pilgrim at-Tijani was told she belonged to the [[Luwata|L\u016bw\u0101ta]] tribe.<ref>at-Tijani, Arabic text p. 57: ''al-k\u0101hinat al-ma'ar\u016bfat bi-k\u0101hinat l\u016bw\u0101tat'', p. 118 of the translation</ref> When the later historian Ibn Khaldun came to write his account, he placed her with the Jarawa tribe.\n\nAccording to various Muslim sources, al-K\u0101hinat was the daughter of [[Tabat]], or some say M\u0101tiya.<ref>According to some, this name is an Arabicized form of the Christian name Matthias or Matthew. See Talbi (1971) for more discussion.</ref> These sources depend on [[tribal]] [[genealogies]], which were generally concocted for political reasons during the 9th century.<ref>Talbi (1971) and Mod\u00e9ran (2005) discuss the various sources.</ref>\n\nIbn Khaldun records many legends about Dihy\u0101. A number of them refer to her long [[hair]] or great size, both legendary characteristics of [[Magician (paranormal)|sorcerers]]. She is also supposed to have had the gift of [[prophecy]] and she had three sons, which is characteristic of witches in legends. Even the fact that two were her own and one was adopted (an [[Arab]] officer she had captured) was an alleged trait of sorcerers in tales. Another [[legend]] claims that in her youth, she had supposedly freed her people from a [[tyrant]] by agreeing to marry him and then murdering him on their [[wedding]] night. Virtually nothing else of her personal life is known.{{According to whom|date=May 2016}}\n\n== Conflicts and legends ==\n\nDihya succeeded [[Kusaila]] as the war leader of the [[Berber people|Berber]] tribes in the 680s and opposed the encroaching Arab Islamic armies of the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad Dynasty]]. [[Hasan ibn al-Nu'man]] marched from [[Egypt]] and captured the major [[Byzantine]] city of [[Carthage]] and other cities (see [[Muslim conquest of the Maghreb|Muslim conquest of North Africa]]). Searching for another enemy to defeat, he was told that the most powerful monarch in North Africa was \"the Queen of the Berbers\" (Arabic: ''malikat al-barbar'') Dihy\u0101, and accordingly marched into [[Numidia]]. In 698, the armies met near [[Meskiana]]<ref>Talbi (1971) suggests that based on the topography reported by al-M\u0101lik\u012b, the actual battlefield was the Wadi N\u012bn\u012b.</ref> in the present-day province of [[Oum el-Bouaghi Province|Oum el-Bouaghi]] at the {{ill|Battle of Meskiana|fr|Bataille de l'oued Nini}} (or \"battle of camels\") in [[Algeria]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Philippe S\u00e9nac|author2=Patrice Cressier|title=Histoire du Maghreb m\u00e9di\u00e9val: VIIe-XIe si\u00e8cle|editor=Armand Colin|year=2012|page=111|language=French|isbn=}}</ref> She defeated Hasan so soundly that he fled [[Ifriqiya]] and holed up in [[Cyrenaica]] (Libya) for four or five years. Realizing that the enemy was too powerful and bound to return, she was said to have embarked on a [[scorched earth]] campaign, which had little impact on the mountain and desert tribes, but lost her the crucial support of the sedentary oasis-dwellers. Instead of discouraging the Arab armies, her desperate decision hastened defeat.<ref>However, even if true, the Arab accounts are considered to be greatly exaggerated. See Talbi (1971) and Mod\u00e9ran (2005). One thing that is certain is that Dihy\u0101 loved ornithology.</ref>\n\nThe story of the Kahina is told by a variety of cultures, and each story often offers a different, or even contradictory, perspective. For example, the story is used to promote feminist beliefs. Additionally, it is even told by Arabs to promote their own nationalism. For the Arabs, they told the story in a perspective that made the Kahina seem like a sorcerer, all in an attempt to discredit her. Some Arab historians took it even farther by saying that the Kahina eventually tried to have her sons adopt Islam as their religion. Another group that told the story of the Kahina was the French. The story of the Kahina was told to paint colonialism in a positive light. The story was told with a message saying that it represented the freeing of Berbers from the Arabs.<ref name=Becker>Becker, Cynthia, [http://www.mizanproject.org/the-kahina-the-female-face-of-berber-history/#_ftn2 \"The Kahina: The Female Face of Berber History\"]. Mizan Project. October 26, 2015. Accessed April 15, 2018.</ref>\n\nAnother, lesser known account of Dihy\u0101 claimed that she had an interest in early studies of desert birds. While this view may or may not be plausible, some evidence has been recovered at the site of her death place, modern-day Algeria. Several fragments of early parchment with a painting of a bird on them were found, although there's no way to conclude the fragments were hers. However, it is possible that she began her interest while in Libya, as the painting was of a Libyan bird species.{{According to whom|date=May 2016}}\n\n== Defeat and death ==\n\n[[Hasan ibn al-Nu'man|Hasan]] eventually returned and, aided by communications with the captured officer \"Khalid bin Yazid al-Qaysi\" adopted by Dihya, defeated her at [[Tabarka]] (a locality in present-day [[Tunisia]] near the [[Algeria]]n borders)<ref name=\"EB1306\" /> about which there is some uncertainty.<ref>Talbi (1971) suggests it was between Setif and Tobna but this is not certain.</ref> According to some accounts, Dihya died fighting the invaders, sword in hand, a warrior's death. Other accounts say she committed suicide by swallowing poison rather than be taken by the enemy. This final act occurred in the 690s or 700s, with 703 CE given as the most likely year.<ref name=\"EB1306\" /> In that year, she was, according to [[Ibn Khaldun]], 127 years old. This is evidently yet another of the many myths which surround her.\n\nAccording to many historians,{{Who|date=June 2018}}{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} her sons Bagay and Khanchla converted, and led the Berber army to [[Iberia]]. However, the historian [[Ali ibn al-Athir|Ibn al-Ath\u012br]] says they died with their mother.\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{refimprove|section|date=January 2017}}\n\nIn later centuries, Dihy\u0101's legend was used to bolster the claims of Berbers in [[al-Andalus]] against Arab claims of ethnic supremacy\u2014in the early modern age, she was used by French colonials, Berber nationalists, North African Jews, North African feminists, and Maghrebi nationalists alike for their own didactic purposes.\n\nIn the present day, the image of the Kahina is constantly used by Berber activists to showcase how they, as a people, are strong and will not be conquered or diminished by other communities. Her face is often seen in graffiti and sculptures around Algeria to showcase their support for the progressive ideals she represents. While her true appearance is still unknown, artists have depicted her with certain aspects that reinforce the progressive movement she is known to represent. However, not all governments accept the ideals behind the Kahina. One statue of the Kahina in Bagha\u00ef was condemned by the government due to blasphemy. The president said that the Kahina represented the resistance of Islam, and thus, should be condemned.<ref name=Becker />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|History|Feminism}}\n* [[Umayyad conquest of North Africa]]\n* [[Kusaila]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Ibn Khaldun]], ''Kit\u0101b al-Ibar''. Usually cited as: ''Histoire des Berb\u00e8res et des dynasties musulmanes de l'Afrique septentrionale'', a French trans. by William McGuckin de Slane, Paul Geuthner, Paris, 1978. This 19th-century translation should now be regarded as obsolete. There is a more accurate modern French translation by Abdesselam Cheddadi, ''Peuples et Nations du Monde: extraits des Ibar'', Sindbad, Paris, 1986 & 1995. Hirschberg (1963) gives an English translation of the section where [[Ibn Khaldun]] discusses the supposed Judaized Jar\u0101wa.\n* Hannoum, Abdelmajid. (2001). ''Post-Colonial Memories: The Legend of the Dihy\u0101, a North African Heroine'' (''Studies in [[African literature|African Literature]]''). {{ISBN|0-325-00253-3}}. This is a study of the legend of the Dihy\u0101 in the 19th century and later. The first chapter is a detailed critique of how the legend of the Dihy\u0101 emerged after several transformations from the 9th century to the 14th.\n* {{Cite journal|last=Hirschberg|first=H.Z.|date=November 1963|title=The Problem of the Judaized Berbers|journal=The Journal of African History|language=en|volume=4|issue=3|pages=313\u2013339|doi=10.1017/S0021853700004278|issn=1469-5138}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LcxtAAAAMAAJ|title=A History of the Jews in North Africa|last=Hirschberg|first=H.Z.|publisher=Brill|year=1974|isbn=978-9004038202|edition=2nd ed., Eng. trans.|volume=Volume 1 From Antiquity to the Sixteenth Century|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n* al-M\u0101lik\u012b, ''Riy\u0101d an-Nuf\u016bs''. Partial French trans. (including the story of the Dihy\u0101) by H.R. Idris, 'Le r\u00e9cit d'al-M\u0101lik\u012b sur la Conqu\u00eate de l'Ifr\u012bqiya', ''Revue des Etudes Islamiques'' 37 (1969) 117\u2013149. The accuracy of this translation has been criticised by Talbi (1971) and others.\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|year=2005|title=Kahena|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e9die berb\u00e8re]]|publisher=Edisud|chapter-url=https://journals.openedition.org/encyclopedieberbere/1306|last=Mod\u00e9ran|first=Yves|authorlink=Yves Mod\u00e9ran|location=Aix-en-Provence|volume=27 {{!}} Kairouan \u2013 Kifan Bel-Ghomari|pages=4102\u20134111|isbn=978-2744905384|chapter=Kahena. (Al-K\u00e2hina)}} The most recent critical study of the historical sources.\n* Talbi, Mohammed. (1971). ''Un nouveau fragment de l'histoire de l'Occident musulman (62\u2013196/682\u2013812) : l'\u00e9pop\u00e